            "thought": "## Architecture of the rewrite\n\n### Layer 1: Lexer (query_t::lexer_t)\n\nThe lexer's job: iterate over the argument sequence and produce tokens. Key changes:\n\n**Remove gotos entirely.** Replace with a proper loop structure:\n- Outer loop: advance through arguments when current is exhausted\n- Inner: character-by-character scanning with clean switch/if-else\n\n**Minimize context dependence.** Currently `tok_context` affects the lexer in these ways:\n1. `TOK_EXPR` context: `(` sets `consume_whitespace=true`, `)` clears it — only for `multiple_args=false`\n2. `TOK_EXPR` context: operators like `@`, `#`, `%`, `=` are included in identifiers instead of being token boundaries\n3. `consume_next_arg`: whole-argument consumption for `expr` in multi-arg mode\n\nThese can be preserved as a cleaner \"lexer mode\" concept rather than scattered flags. But we need to keep the `next_token(tok_context)` signature for API compatibility.\n\n**Clean up identifier accumulation.** Instead of accumulating with embedded whitespace and stripping, use a cleaner approach:\n- When `multiple_args=true`: each argument is scanned independently. Operator characters break tokens. No whitespace accumulation needed (whitespace within a single arg that's NOT an operator should be included in the token, but this only happens in edge cases).\n- When `multiple_args=false`: whitespace is a token separator (unless in expr paren context).\n\nActually wait — I need to be more careful. The current behavior of whitespace in multi-arg mode is that ALL characters between arg_i and arg_end within a single argument get accumulated into the identifier (including spaces), then trailing spaces are stripped. This means an argument like `\"food and bar\"` in multi-arg mode would accumulate `\"food and bar\"`, then check if it starts with \"expr\" — and if not, it would become TERM(\"food and bar\") after stripping trailing spaces.\n\nBut that's wrong for the test case `testPredicateTokenizer1`: `[\"foo\", \"and\", \"bar\"]` produces TERM, TOK_AND, TERM. Each is a separate argument, so \"foo\" is one arg, \"and\" is another, \"bar\" is another. The lexer exhausts \"foo\" (the whole arg), then advances to \"and\" (recognized as keyword), then \"bar\".\n\nFor `testPredicateTokenizer2`: `[\"foo and bar\"]` with `multiple_args=false` — here spaces break tokens because `!multiple_args && !consume_whitespace` → goto test_ident.\n\nOK so in `multiple_args=true` mode, within a single argument:\n- Whitespace is accumulated in the identifier\n- Then trailing whitespace stripped  \n- Then the identifier is checked for the \"expr\" prefix\n- Then keyword matching\n\nSo `\"food and bar\"` as a single arg in multi-arg mode would become TERM(\"food and bar\"). That's the correct behavior — it's treated as one pattern because it was a single shell argument.\n\nBut what about `\"(food\"` as a single arg? The `(` is caught in Phase 3 before identifier accumulation starts. So `(` returns LPAREN, then `food` continues from where we left off in the same arg.\n\nThis is actually not too bad. The key insight: in multi-arg mode, operator characters within an arg are still recognized as tokens (they break the identifier). The difference from single-arg mode is only that whitespace does NOT break tokens.\n\n### Refactored Lexer Design\n\n```cpp\ntoken_t next_token(token_t::kind_t tok_context) {\n  // 1. Return cached token if any\n  // 2. Skip to next non-exhausted argument\n  // 3. Skip leading whitespace (in single-arg mode only)\n  // 4. Check for quoted patterns: '...', \"...\", /.../ \n  // 5. Check for whole-arg consumption (expr in multi-arg mode)\n  // 6. Check single-char operators: (, ), &, |, !, @, #, %, =, backslash\n  // 7. Accumulate identifier (bare word):\n  //    - Stop at operator chars (unless in expr context or after backslash)\n  //    - Stop at whitespace (in single-arg mode only)\n  //    - Stop at end of argument\n  // 8. Match identifier against keywords