          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>ae46********c549</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********EyT5</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/ae4618e0fe994c549.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Community best practices research\" completed</summary>\n<result>The search tool is currently unavailable (authentication issue). However, this is a topic where I have deep knowledge from my training data. Let me provide a thorough, research-grade synthesis of community best practices across all five areas.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Modern C++ Recursive-Descent Parser Patterns (C++17/20)\n\n### The Core Architecture: Separate Lexer, Token Stream, Parser\n\nThe consensus across production parsers (Clang, V8, GCC's C++ frontend, Rust's `rustc`) is a clean three-layer architecture:\n\n```\nInput Source --> Lexer --> Token Stream --> Parser --> AST\n```\n\n**Key principle**: The parser never touches raw characters. It operates entirely on typed tokens.\n\n### Token Representation\n\nUse `std::variant` (C++17) or a tagged union for tokens. Avoid inheritance hierarchies for tokens -- they are value types, not polymorphic objects.\n\n```cpp\nstruct source_location {\n  std::string_view source_name;  // filename, \"<command-line>\", etc.\n  std::uint32_t    offset;       // byte offset into source\n  std::uint16_t    line;\n  std::uint16_t    column;\n};\n\nstruct source_range {\n  source_location begin;\n  source_location end;\n};\n\nenum class token_kind : std::uint8_t {\n  // Literals\n  tok_string,\n  tok_regex,\n  tok_date,\n  tok_amount,\n\n  // Keywords\n  tok_and,\n  tok_or,\n  tok_not,\n\n  // Punctuation\n  tok_lparen,\n  tok_rparen,\n  tok_at,\n  tok_slash,\n\n  // Special\n  tok_eof,\n  tok_error,  // lexer-produced error token\n};\n\nstruct token {\n  token_kind    kind;\n  std::string_view text;     // view into original source\n  source_range  range;\n\n  // For tokens carrying semantic value:\n  std::variant<\n    std::monostate,          // most tokens\n    std::string,             // string literals (after unescaping)\n    date_t,                  // parsed dates\n    amount_t                 // parsed amounts\n  > value;\n};\n```\n\n**Why `std::string_view` for `text`**: The lexer should not allocate unless it must (e.g., string unescaping). Views into the original input buffer are zero-cost.\n\n### Parser Structure: Each Grammar Rule = One Method\n\nThe fundamental pattern maps each grammar production to a method returning an AST node. Use `std::unique_ptr<T>` for AST ownership and `std::optional<T>` or `nullptr` for \"no match.\"\n\n```cpp\nclass parser {\n  lexer&  lex_;\n  token   current_;  // one-token lookahead\n\n  // Token consumption primitives\n  token peek() const { return current_; }\n  token advance() { auto prev = current_; current_ = lex_.next(); return prev; }\n  bool  check(token_kind k) const { return current_.kind == k; }\n  bool  match(token_kind k) { if (check(k)) { advance(); return true; } return false; }\n  token expect(token_kind k, std::string_view msg);\n\npublic:\n  // Grammar rules\n  std::unique_ptr<query_node> parse_query();\n\nprivate:\n  std::unique_ptr<query_node> parse_or_expr();\n  std::unique_ptr<query_node> parse_and_expr();\n  std::unique_ptr<query_node> parse_unary_expr();\n  std::unique_ptr<query_node> parse_primary();\n  std::unique_ptr<query_node> parse_term(query_kind prefix);\n};\n```\n\n### The `expect` Pattern\n\nThis is the single most important error-reporting primitive:\n\n```cpp\ntoken parser::expect(token_kind k, std::string_view msg) {\n  if (check(k))\n    return advance();\n  throw parse_error(current_.range.begin, msg,\n                    fmt::format(\"expected {}, found '{}'\",\n                                token_kind_name(k), current_.text));\n}\n```\n\n### Pratt Parsing for Expressions (If Needed)\n\nIf the query language has infix operators with precedence, Pratt parsing (top-down operator precedence) is the modern standard. It avoids deeply nested `parse_add -> parse_mul -> parse_unary` chains:\n\n```cpp\nstd::unique_ptr<expr_node> parser::parse_expr(int min_precedence) {\n  auto left = parse_prefix();\n  while (precedence_of(peek().kind) >= min_precedence) {\n    auto op = advance();\n    int prec = precedence_of(op.kind);\n    int next_min = is_right_assoc(op.kind) ? prec : prec + 1;\n    auto right = parse_expr(next_min);\n    left = std::make_unique<binary_node>(op.kind, std::move(left), std::move(right));\n  }\n  return left;\n}\n```\n\n### C++17/20 Specific Patterns\n\n- **`std::string_view`** everywhere for non-owning string references (C++17)\n- **`std::variant`** for token values and AST node payloads (C++17)\n- **`std::optional<T>`** for nullable parse results instead of raw pointers (C++17)\n- **Structured bindings** for destructuring tokens (C++17)\n- **`constexpr` keyword tables** using `std::array` and compile-time sorting (C++17/20)\n- **`std::span<const std::string>`** for argument lists (C++20, or use a range)\n- **Concepts** to constrain template parameters on input sources (C++20)\n\n---\n\n## 2. Lexer Design for Multi-Source Input\n\n### The Problem\n\nThe parser must handle two input modes:\n1. Multiple command-line arguments: `[\"payee\", \"grocery\", \"and\", \"amount>50\"]`\n2. A single query string: `\"payee grocery and amount>50\"`\n\nThese must produce identical token streams.\n\n### Pattern: Abstract Input Cursor\n\nDefine a cursor abstraction that both sources implement. The lexer operates on this cursor, never on raw strings directly.\n\n```cpp\nclass input_cursor {\npublic:\n  virtual ~input_cursor() = default;\n\n  virtual char peek() const = 0;        // current char, or '\\0' at end\n  virtual char advance() = 0;           // consume and return current char\n  virtual bool at_end() const = 0;\n  virtual source_location location() const = 0;\n\n  // For multi-arg mode: is this a \"hard\" word boundary (argument break)\n  // vs a \"soft\" boundary (whitespace within one argument)?\n  virtual bool at_arg_boundary() const { return false; }\n};\n```\n\n### Implementation 1: Single-String Cursor\n\n```cpp\nclass string_cursor : public input_cursor {\n  std::string_view input_;\n  std::size_t      pos_ = 0;\n  std::uint16_t    line_ = 1;\n  std::uint16_t    col_  = 1;\n\npublic:\n  explicit string_cursor(std::string_view input) : input_(input) {}\n\n  char peek() const override {\n    return pos_ < input_.size() ? input_[pos_] : '\\0';\n  }\n  char advance() override {\n    char c = input_[pos_++];\n    if (c == '\\n') { ++line_; col_ = 1; } else { ++col_; }\n    return c;\n  }\n  bool at_end() const override { return pos_ >= input_.size(); }\n  source_location location() const override {\n    return {\"<query>\", static_cast<uint32_t>(pos_), line_, col_};\n  }\n};\n```\n\n### Implementation 2: Argument-List Cursor\n\nThe key insight: treat argument boundaries as implicit whitespace.\n\n```cpp\nclass argv_cursor : public input_cursor {\n  std::span<const std::string> args_;\n  std::size_t arg_idx_ = 0;\n  std::size_t char_idx_ = 0;\n  bool        at_boundary_ = false;\n\npublic:\n  explicit argv_cursor(std::span<const std::string> args) : args_(args) {}\n\n  char peek() const override {\n    if (arg_idx_ >= args_.size()) return '\\0';\n    if (char_idx_ >= args_[arg_idx_].size()) return ' ';  // synthetic space\n    return args_[arg_idx_][char_idx_];\n  }\n\n  char advance() override {\n    if (char_idx_ >= args_[arg_idx_].size()) {\n      // Move to next argument\n      ++arg_idx_;\n      char_idx_ = 0;\n      at_boundary_ = true;\n      return ' ';  // synthetic space between arguments\n    }\n    at_boundary_ = false;\n    return args_[arg_idx_][char_idx_++];\n  }\n\n  bool at_arg_boundary() const override { return at_boundary_; }\n  // ... other methods\n};\n```\n\n### Alternative: Pre-Normalize to a Single Buffer\n\nA simpler approach used by many production systems: join the arguments into one string with separators, then lex that. This avoids the virtual dispatch overhead and simplifies the lexer.\n\n```cpp\nstruct normalized_input {\n  std::string buffer;\n  std::vector<std::size_t> arg_boundaries;  // offsets where args were joined\n\n  static normalized_input from_argv(std::span<const std::string> args) {\n    normalized_input result;\n    for (std::size_t i = 0; i < args.size(); ++i) {\n      if (i > 0) {\n        result.arg_boundaries.push_back(result.buffer.size());\n        result.buffer += ' ';\n      }\n      result.buffer += args[i];\n    }\n    return result;\n  }\n\n  static normalized_input from_string(std::string_view s) {\n    return {std::string(s), {}};\n  }\n};\n```\n\nThe lexer then operates on `buffer` and can check `arg_boundaries` when it matters (e.g., to determine if a space is \"real\" or synthetic).\n\n**Recommendation**: The pre-normalization approach is simpler and more debuggable. Use it unless profiling shows the extra copy is a problem (it will not be for query-sized inputs).\n\n---\n\n## 3. Context-Sensitive Lexing\n\n### The Problem\n\nIn query parsing, the same characters mean different things depending on context:\n- Parentheses might delimit groups in the query language, but be literal inside expression contexts\n- `/` might start a regex or be a division operator\n- Whitespace might be a token separator or part of a payee name\n\n### Pattern 1: Lexer Modes (State Stack)\n\nThis is the standard production approach (used by Flex, ANTLR, Clang for raw string literals, etc.). The lexer maintains a stack of modes, and each mode defines different tokenization rules.\n\n```cpp\nenum class lex_mode {\n  query,       // top-level query: parens group, slashes start regex\n  expr,        // expression context: parens are for grouping expressions\n  regex,       // inside /regex/\n  string,      // inside \"quoted string\"\n};\n\nclass lexer {\n  input_cursor&         input_;\n  std::vector<lex_mode> mode_stack_;\n\npublic:\n  void push_mode(lex_mode m) { mode_stack_.push_back(m); }\n  void pop_mode() { mode_stack_.pop_back(); }\n  lex_mode current_mode() const { return mode_stack_.back(); }\n\n  token next() {\n    skip_whitespace();\n    if (input_.at_end()) return make_token(tok_eof);\n\n    switch (current_mode()) {\n    case lex_mode::query: return lex_query();\n    case lex_mode::expr:  return lex_expr();\n    // ...\n    }\n  }\n\nprivate:\n  token lex_query() {\n    char c = input_.peek();\n    switch (c) {\n    case '(': input_.advance(); return make_token(tok_lparen);\n    case ')': input_.advance(); return make_token(tok_rparen);\n    case '/': return lex_regex();\n    default:  return lex_word();\n    }\n  }\n\n  token lex_expr() {\n    char c = input_.peek();\n    // In expr mode, parentheses don't delimit query groups\n    // They're part of expression syntax, handled by the expression parser\n    switch (c) {\n    case '/': return lex_as_operator(tok_slash);  // division, not regex\n    default:  return lex_expr_token();\n    }\n  }\n};\n```\n\n**Key design rule**: Mode pushes/pops are initiated by the parser, not the lexer. The parser knows the grammar context; the lexer does not.\n\n```cpp\n// In the parser:\nstd::unique_ptr<query_node> parser::parse_expr_term() {\n  expect(tok_expr_keyword);  // e.g., \"expr\"\n  lex_.push_mode(lex_mode::expr);\n  auto result = parse_expression();\n  lex_.pop_mode();\n  return result;\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 2: Token Reinterpretation\n\nInstead of changing lexer behavior, the lexer always produces the same tokens and the parser reinterprets them. This is simpler but only works when the character-level tokenization is the same.\n\n```cpp\n// Lexer always produces tok_lparen for '('\n// Parser decides what it means:\nif (in_expr_context) {\n  // Treat tok_lparen as expression grouping -- parse a sub-expression\n} else {\n  // Treat tok_lparen as query grouping -- parse a sub-query\n}\n```\n\n### Pattern 3: Lexer Callbacks (Cleanest for Complex Cases)\n\nThe lexer calls back to the parser when it encounters ambiguous characters:\n\n```cpp\nclass lexer {\n  std::function<bool()> is_regex_context_;  // set by parser\n\npublic:\n  void set_context_query(std::function<bool()> fn) {\n    is_regex_context_ = std::move(fn);\n  }\n\n  token lex_slash() {\n    if (is_regex_context_ && is_regex_context_())\n      return lex_regex();\n    else\n      return make_token(tok_slash);\n  }\n};\n```\n\n**Recommendation for your case**: Use the mode stack (Pattern 1). It is the most widely used, best understood, and scales cleanly. The mode stack replaces scattered boolean flags with a single, inspectable state. Debug logging becomes trivial:\n\n```cpp\nvoid push_mode(lex_mode m) {\n  TRACE(\"lexer\", \"push mode: \" << mode_name(m));\n  mode_stack_.push_back(m);\n}\n```\n\n### Avoiding State Flag Spaghetti: The Explicit State Table\n\nIf you have many interacting flags, convert them to an explicit state machine. The states are combinations of flags, but named and documented:\n\n```cpp\n// BEFORE (spaghetti):\nbool in_expr_ = false;\nbool in_regex_ = false;\nbool after_keyword_ = false;\n// ... and scattered if-else checks\n\n// AFTER (explicit mode enum):\nenum class lex_mode {\n  query_top,          // top-level query\n  query_after_prefix, // just saw \"payee\", \"account\", etc.\n  expr_body,          // inside expr <...>\n  regex_body,         // inside /.../\n};\n// Single variable replaces all flags\n```\n\n---\n\n## 4. Error Message Quality\n\n### Source Location Tracking\n\nEvery token must carry its source range. This is non-negotiable for good error messages.\n\n```cpp\nstruct source_range {\n  source_location begin;\n  source_location end;\n};\n```\n\nFor command-line query parsing, the \"source\" is the query string or argument list. Include the argument index for multi-arg input.\n\n### The Error Message Template\n\nFollow the Clang/Rust model -- the most praised error messages in the industry:\n\n```\nerror: <what went wrong>\n  --> <source>:<line>:<column>\n   |\n 1 | payee grocery and (amount > 50\n   |                               ^ expected ')' to close group opened at column 19\n```\n\nFor single-line query strings, a simpler caret-based format works well:\n\n```\nerror: unexpected end of query; expected ')' to match '(' at position 19\n  payee grocery and (amount > 50\n                                ^\n```\n\n### Implementation Pattern\n\n```cpp\nstruct parse_error {\n  source_range    location;\n  std::string     message;\n  std::string     detail;          // optional elaboration\n  source_range    related_location; // e.g., the opening paren\n\n  std::string format(std::string_view source_text) const {\n    std::string result;\n    result += fmt::format(\"error: {}\\n\", message);\n\n    // Extract the line containing the error\n    auto [line_text, line_offset] = extract_line(source_text, location.begin.offset);\n    result += fmt::format(\"  {}\\n\", line_text);\n\n    // Caret indicator\n    std::size_t col = location.begin.offset - line_offset;\n    result += fmt::format(\"  {}^ {}\\n\", std::string(col, ' '), detail);\n\n    return result;\n  }\n};\n```\n\n### Error Recovery Strategies\n\nFor a query parser (as opposed to a full programming language), the best strategy is usually **fail fast with a clear message**. However, if you want to report multiple errors:\n\n**Synchronization tokens**: After an error, skip tokens until you reach a \"synchronization point\" (e.g., `and`, `or`, `)`, end of input), then resume parsing.\n\n```cpp\nvoid parser::synchronize() {\n  while (!check(tok_eof)) {\n    if (check(tok_and) || check(tok_or) || check(tok_rparen))\n      return;\n    advance();\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Panic mode with recovery**:\n\n```cpp\nstd::unique_ptr<query_node> parser::parse_primary() {\n  try {\n    if (match(tok_lparen)) {\n      auto inner = parse_or_expr();\n      expect(tok_rparen, \"expected closing ')'\");\n      return inner;\n    }\n    // ... other cases\n  } catch (parse_error& e) {\n    errors_.push_back(std::move(e));\n    synchronize();\n    return std::make_unique<error_node>();  // placeholder\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Contextual Error Messages\n\nThe best parsers include context about what they were trying to do:\n\n```cpp\n// BAD:  \"unexpected token 'and'\"\n// GOOD: \"unexpected 'and' in amount expression; did you mean to close the expression first?\"\n// GOOD: \"expected account name after 'account' keyword, but found 'and'\"\n```\n\nAchieve this by passing context strings down through parse methods:\n\n```cpp\nstd::unique_ptr<query_node> parser::parse_term_argument(query_kind prefix) {\n  if (check(tok_eof) || check(tok_and) || check(tok_or)) {\n    throw parse_error(current_.range.begin,\n      fmt::format(\"expected {} pattern after '{}'\",\n                  query_kind_name(prefix), query_kind_keyword(prefix)));\n  }\n  return parse_pattern();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## 5. Testing Recursive-Descent Parsers\n\n### Layer 1: Unit Tests on the Lexer\n\nTest the lexer in isolation. This catches tokenization bugs early and makes parser debugging much easier.\n\n```cpp\nTEST(Lexer, BasicTokenization) {\n  auto tokens = lex_all(\"payee grocery and @amt > 50\");\n  ASSERT_EQ(tokens.size(), 7);  // including EOF\n  EXPECT_EQ(tokens[0].kind, tok_word);\n  EXPECT_EQ(tokens[0].text, \"payee\");\n  EXPECT_EQ(tokens[1].kind, tok_word);\n  EXPECT_EQ(tokens[1].text, \"grocery\");\n  EXPECT_EQ(tokens[2].kind, tok_and);\n  // ...\n}\n\nTEST(Lexer, ModeSwitching) {\n  lexer lex(make_cursor(\"expr (amount > 50)\"));\n  EXPECT_EQ(lex.next().kind, tok_word);  // \"expr\"\n  lex.push_mode(lex_mode::expr);\n  EXPECT_EQ(lex.next().kind, tok_lparen);  // '(' in expr mode\n  // ...\n}\n```\n\n### Layer 2: Snapshot/Golden-File Tests on Parse Output\n\nParse queries and compare the AST (serialized as a string) against golden files. This is the highest-value test category for parsers.\n\n```cpp\nTEST(Parser, BasicQuery) {\n  auto ast = parse_query(\"payee grocery and account expenses\");\n  EXPECT_EQ(ast->to_string(),\n    \"(and (payee \\\"grocery\\\") (account \\\"expenses\\\"))\");\n}\n\nTEST(Parser, Precedence) {\n  auto ast = parse_query(\"payee a or payee b and account c\");\n  // OR has lower precedence than AND:\n  EXPECT_EQ(ast->to_string(),\n    \"(or (payee \\\"a\\\") (and (payee \\\"b\\\") (account \\\"c\\\")))\");\n}\n```\n\n**Use a `.test` file format** (you already have one in ledger). Each test case is:\n\n```\nquery: payee grocery and account expenses\nast: (and (payee \"grocery\") (account \"expenses\"))\n---\nquery: not payee grocery\nast: (not (payee \"grocery\"))\n```\n\n### Layer 3: Round-Trip / Equivalence Tests\n\nIf you can serialize the AST back to a query string, verify:\n\n```\nparse(input).to_query_string() --> re-parse --> same AST\n```\n\nThis catches serialization bugs and also serves as a property test.\n\n### Layer 4: Error Message Tests\n\nTest that bad inputs produce the expected error messages. These are snapshot tests on the error output:\n\n```cpp\nTEST(Parser, ErrorMessages) {\n  auto result = try_parse(\"payee grocery and\");\n  ASSERT_FALSE(result.ok());\n  EXPECT_THAT(result.error().message,\n    HasSubstr(\"expected query term after 'and'\"));\n}\n\nTEST(Parser, MismatchedParen) {\n  auto result = try_parse(\"(payee grocery\");\n  ASSERT_FALSE(result.ok());\n  EXPECT_THAT(result.error().message,\n    HasSubstr(\"expected ')'\"));\n}\n```\n\n### Layer 5: Property-Based Testing (Fuzzing)\n\nFor parsers, fuzzing is exceptionally valuable because the input space is complex.\n\n**Grammar-based fuzzing**: Generate random valid queries from the grammar, parse them, and verify no crashes or assertion failures.\n\n```cpp\n// Using a fuzzing library (libFuzzer, AFL):\nextern \"C\" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t* data, size_t size) {\n  std::string input(reinterpret_cast<const char*>(data), size);\n  try {\n    auto ast = parse_query(input);\n    // If it parsed, verify invariants:\n    if (ast) {\n      ASSERT(ast->is_well_formed());\n      // Round-trip test:\n      auto reparsed = parse_query(ast->to_string());\n      ASSERT(ast->structurally_equal(*reparsed));\n    }\n  } catch (const parse_error&) {\n    // Expected for random input -- just don't crash\n  }\n  return 0;\n}\n```\n\n**Property: argv vs. string equivalence**: For your multi-source input, a powerful property test is:\n\n```cpp\n// Splitting a query string on spaces and parsing as argv\n// should produce the same AST as parsing the original string\n// (with caveats for quoted strings spanning spaces)\nvoid test_input_equivalence(const std::string& query) {\n  auto ast1 = parse_query_string(query);\n  auto args = split_on_spaces(query);  // naive split\n  auto ast2 = parse_query_argv(args);\n  ASSERT_EQ(ast1->to_string(), ast2->to_string());\n}\n```\n\n### Layer 6: Integration Tests\n\nTest the parser as part of the full pipeline (what your `.test` files already do): given a journal and a query, verify the correct output.\n\n### Test Organization Summary\n\n| Layer | What it tests | Tool | Count |\n|-------|--------------|------|-------|\n| Lexer unit | Tokenization correctness | Unit test framework | ~30-50 |\n| AST snapshot | Parse tree structure | Golden file comparison | ~50-100 |\n| Error messages | Error reporting quality | Snapshot comparison | ~20-30 |\n| Round-trip | Serialization fidelity | Property test | ~10 + generator |\n| Fuzz | Crash resistance | libFuzzer/AFL | Continuous |\n| Integration | End-to-end correctness | `.test` harness | ~20-50 |\n\n---\n\n## Key References\n\n1. **\"Crafting Interpreters\" by Robert Nystrom** (craftinginterpreters.com) -- The modern standard reference for hand-written recursive-descent parsers. Chapter 6 (parsing expressions) and Chapter 16 (scanning) are directly applicable. Free online.\n\n2. **Clang's Lexer/Parser architecture** -- Production C++ recursive-descent parser. Source in `clang/lib/Lex/` and `clang/lib/Parse/`. The `Parser::ExpectAndConsume` pattern and diagnostic system are worth studying.\n\n3. **\"Simple but Powerful Pratt Parsing\" by Alex Kladov (matklad)** (matklad.github.io/2020/04/15/simple-but-powerful-pratt-parsing.html) -- Concise, practical guide to Pratt parsing. Rust code but directly translatable to C++.\n\n4. **\"From Recursive Descent to Pratt Parsing\" by Bob Nystrom** (journal.stuffwithstuff.com/2011/03/19/pratt-parsers-expression-parsing-made-easy/) -- Bridges the gap between RD and Pratt approaches.\n\n5. **Rust compiler's lexer modes** (`rustc_lexer`) -- Clean implementation of context-sensitive lexing with mode stacks. Well-documented.\n\n6. **\"Compiler Error Messages Considered Unhelpful\" (Becker et al., 2019)** -- Academic study of what makes error messages helpful. Key finding: state what was expected, state what was found, suggest a fix.\n\n---\n\n## Summary of Recommendations for Your Query Parser\n\n1. **Architecture**: Clean separation -- `input_cursor` (or pre-normalized buffer) -> `lexer` (produces tokens) -> `parser` (produces AST). The parser never sees raw characters.\n\n2. **Multi-source input**: Pre-normalize argv into a single buffer with boundary markers. Simpler than virtual dispatch and equally correct for query-sized inputs.\n\n3. **Context sensitivity**: Use an explicit lexer mode stack, pushed/popped by the parser. Replace boolean flags with named enum values. This is the single biggest maintainability improvement over flag-based approaches.\n\n4. **Error messages**: Every token carries source location. Errors state what was expected, what was found, and (where possible) what the user might have meant. Use the caret-under-source format.\n\n5. **Testing**: Invest most heavily in AST snapshot tests (highest value-to-effort ratio). Add lexer unit tests, error message snapshots, and at least a basic fuzzer. The argv/string equivalence property test is cheap and high-value for your specific case.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>7300</total_tokens><tool_uses>3</tool_uses><duration_ms>132575</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/ae4618e0fe994c549.output",
