          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a316********e1eb</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********NSKZ</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/a316bcdd1bc6ae1eb.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Prior art: existing parser solutions\" completed</summary>\n<result>The Perplexity search API is returning authorization errors. I will provide this research based on my existing knowledge, which covers these topics thoroughly up to my training cutoff. Let me structure the findings across all four research areas.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Similar Query Languages in Other CLI Tools\n\n### Lucene / Elasticsearch Query Syntax\n\nLucene's query parser is the most direct analog to ledger's query language. The parallels are striking:\n\n| Lucene Feature | Ledger Equivalent |\n|---|---|\n| `field:value` | `@payee`, `#code`, `%meta` |\n| `\"exact phrase\"` | `'foo'`, `\"foo\"` |\n| `AND`, `OR`, `NOT` | `and`, `or`, `not` |\n| `+required -excluded` | implicit `and`, `not` |\n| Grouping with `()` | Parenthesized sub-expressions |\n\nLucene's classic query parser is implemented as a JavaCC grammar (~200 lines of grammar definition). The key design insight: **field prefixes are handled in the lexer, not the grammar**. The lexer emits a `FIELD` token when it sees `word:`, and the parser consumes `FIELD VALUE` as a unit. This keeps the grammar simple.\n\nSource code reference: `lucene/queryparser/src/java/org/apache/lucene/queryparser/classic/QueryParser.jj` in the Apache Lucene repository on GitHub.\n\nThe modern \"simple query parser\" in Lucene uses a hand-written recursive descent parser (class `SimpleQueryParser`) that is approximately 400 lines of Java. It handles `+`, `-`, `\"phrases\"`, `(grouping)`, `|` (OR), `~N` (fuzzy), and `*` (prefix). This is a good model for what a hand-written parser for ledger's grammar would look like.\n\n### SQLite FTS5\n\nFTS5's query syntax supports:\n\n- Column filters: `column:term`\n- Boolean: `AND`, `OR`, `NOT`\n- Phrases: `\"multi word\"`\n- Prefix: `term*`\n- Grouping: `( )`\n\nFTS5's parser is hand-written C in `fts5_expr.c` (~1500 lines, but includes the expression evaluator too). The tokenizer is about 200 lines. The key pattern: **it uses a Pratt parser (top-down operator precedence)** for boolean expressions, which is elegant for handling `AND`/`OR`/`NOT` precedence. The implicit operator between adjacent terms is `AND`, similar to how ledger treats adjacent query terms.\n\nReference: `ext/fts5/fts5_expr.c` in the SQLite source tree (public domain, freely studiable).\n\n### Ripgrep (rg) and ag\n\nThese tools do not have a structured query language per se -- they use PCRE/regex patterns with command-line flags (`--type`, `--glob`, `-w`). The filtering logic is composed at the CLI argument level, not parsed from a query string. Not directly applicable.\n\n### Git log filtering\n\nGit's `--grep`, `--author`, `--after` etc. are also CLI-flag-based rather than parsed from a query string. However, `git log`'s `--all-match` vs default (any match) behavior and the `--not` revision flag show a pattern where boolean logic is expressed through flag combinations. The `revision.c` pathspec parsing is closer to a query language but is highly git-specific.\n\n### jq\n\njq has a full programming language, not a query/filter DSL. Its parser is generated by Bison (`parser.y`, ~600 lines of grammar). Overkill for comparison, but the jq lexer's handling of string interpolation and the `.field` accessor syntax is interesting if you ever want to support nested field access.\n\n### Key Takeaway from CLI Tools\n\nFor a grammar of ledger's complexity (~15 productions, boolean operators, field prefixes, quoted strings), the two dominant approaches in successful tools are:\n\n1. **Hand-written recursive descent** (Lucene SimpleQueryParser, SQLite FTS5) -- preferred when the grammar is small and control over error messages matters.\n2. **Pratt parser for expression precedence** (FTS5) -- elegant for `and`/`or`/`not` with different precedence levels.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Ledger-Like Tools: hledger and Beancount\n\n### hledger Query Parser\n\nhledger's query language is the closest analog. It supports:\n\n- `acct:REGEX` (account), `desc:REGEX` (description/payee), `tag:NAME=VALUE`\n- `not:`, `date:`, `amt:`, `status:`, `code:`, `note:`\n- Boolean: terms are implicitly ANDed; `not:` prefix negates a single term\n- No explicit `or` operator (unlike ledger)\n\nThe parser is in Haskell: `Hledger/Query.hs` (approximately 500 lines). Key design points:\n\n- The query string is first **split into words** respecting quotes (a simple state-machine tokenizer).\n- Each word is then classified by prefix (`acct:`, `desc:`, `not:`, etc.) using pattern matching.\n- The result is an AST type: `data Query = Any | None | Not Query | And [Query] | Or [Query] | Acct Regexp | ...`\n- Boolean combination is implicit: all terms are `And`-ed together.\n\nThis is essentially a **keyword-prefix tokenizer + trivial parser** because there is no operator precedence to deal with (no infix `or`).\n\nhledger source reference: `https://github.com/simonmichael/hledger/blob/master/hledger-lib/Hledger/Query.hs`\n\n### Beancount Query Language (BQL)\n\nBeancount takes a radically different approach: its query language is **SQL-like**:\n\n```\nSELECT date, narration, account, position WHERE account ~ 'Expenses' AND date >= 2024-01-01\n```\n\nThe parser is generated by **PLY (Python Lex-Yacc)** in `beanquery/parser/parser.py` and `beanquery/parser/lexer.py`. The grammar is approximately 200 productions -- far more complex than needed for ledger's query syntax because it supports `SELECT`, `GROUP BY`, `ORDER BY`, `PIVOT`, aggregate functions, etc.\n\nSource reference: `https://github.com/beancount/beanquery` (the query component was extracted into its own package).\n\n### Plain-Text Accounting Query Patterns\n\nLooking across the PTA ecosystem, there are three tiers of query complexity:\n\n1. **Simple prefix/term** (hledger): Split on whitespace, classify by prefix, implicit AND. No real parser needed.\n2. **Boolean with field prefixes** (ledger): Needs a real parser for `and`/`or`/`not`/parentheses plus the field-prefix and section-keyword features.\n3. **Full SQL** (beancount/beanquery): Requires a grammar-generated parser.\n\nLedger sits squarely in tier 2, which is the sweet spot for either a hand-written recursive descent parser or a small PEG grammar.\n\n### Key Takeaway from Accounting Tools\n\nhledger's approach (split-and-classify) is too simple for ledger because ledger has explicit boolean operators and section keywords (`show`, `only`, `for`, etc.). Beancount's SQL approach is too heavyweight. The right model is a small recursive descent parser, possibly with a Pratt parser core for boolean expressions.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Boost.Spirit Alternatives: C++ Parser Combinator Libraries\n\n### The Compile-Time Problem with Boost.Spirit\n\nBoost.Spirit X3 (the modern version) is known for:\n- Heavy template instantiation: a simple grammar can generate thousands of template specializations\n- Compile times of 10-30 seconds for modest grammars (measured repeatedly in benchmarks)\n- Excellent runtime performance (often competitive with hand-written parsers)\n- Complex error messages when things go wrong\n\nFor a grammar with ~15 productions, Spirit X3 is workable but brings significant compile-time cost to a project that already uses Boost heavily.\n\n### PEGTL (Parsing Expression Grammar Template Library)\n\n**Repository**: `https://github.com/taocpp/PEGTL`\n\n- Header-only, C++17\n- Grammar rules are C++ types (one class per rule), matched by template specialization\n- **Compile time**: Significantly better than Spirit X3. For a 15-production grammar, expect 2-5 seconds.\n- **Runtime**: Competitive with hand-written; the library uses template-based dispatch that compiles down to efficient code.\n- **Error handling**: Built-in support for custom error messages via `must<>` rules and control classes.\n- **Code size**: A PEGTL grammar for ledger's query language would be approximately 100-150 lines of rule definitions plus 100-200 lines of actions.\n\nExample of what a boolean expression grammar looks like in PEGTL:\n\n```cpp\nnamespace query {\n  struct ws : pegtl::star<pegtl::space> {};\n  struct quoted_string : pegtl::seq<\n    pegtl::one<'\\''>,\n    pegtl::star<pegtl::not_one<'\\''>>,\n    pegtl::one<'\\''>\n  > {};\n  struct field_prefix : pegtl::seq<\n    pegtl::one<'@', '#', '%', '='>,\n    pegtl::identifier\n  > {};\n  struct not_op : pegtl::keyword<'n','o','t'> {};\n  struct and_op : pegtl::keyword<'a','n','d'> {};\n  struct or_op  : pegtl::keyword<'o','r'> {};\n  struct atom : pegtl::sor<field_prefix, quoted_string, pegtl::identifier> {};\n  struct expr;\n  struct primary : pegtl::sor<\n    pegtl::seq<pegtl::one<'('>, ws, expr, ws, pegtl::one<')'>>,\n    pegtl::seq<not_op, ws, primary>,\n    atom\n  > {};\n  struct and_expr : pegtl::list<primary, pegtl::seq<ws, and_op, ws>> {};\n  struct expr : pegtl::list<and_expr, pegtl::seq<ws, or_op, ws>> {};\n}\n```\n\n### Lexy\n\n**Repository**: `https://github.com/foonathan/lexy`\n\n- Header-only, C++17 (some features require C++20)\n- **Key differentiator**: Designed specifically for good error reporting. The error messages are part of the grammar definition.\n- **Compile time**: Better than Spirit, comparable to PEGTL (2-5 seconds for small grammars).\n- **Design philosophy**: \"Parsing as the dual of formatting.\" Grammars look like format strings.\n- **Maturity**: Less mature than PEGTL (first release 2020 vs PEGTL's 2014), but actively maintained.\n\nExample snippet:\n\n```cpp\nstruct query_expr {\n  struct or_op {\n    static constexpr auto rule = LEXY_LIT(\"or\");\n  };\n  static constexpr auto rule = dsl::list(\n    dsl::p<and_expr>,\n    dsl::sep(dsl::p<or_op>)\n  );\n  static constexpr auto value = lexy::fold_inplace<std::vector<node>>(\n    [] { return std::vector<node>{}; },\n    [](auto& vec, node&& n) { vec.push_back(std::move(n)); }\n  );\n};\n```\n\n### cpp-peglib\n\n**Repository**: `https://github.com/yhirose/cpp-peglib`\n\n- Header-only, C++17\n- **Key differentiator**: PEG grammar is specified as a **runtime string**, not compiled templates. This means near-zero compile-time overhead.\n- **Trade-off**: Runtime grammar compilation (one-time cost at startup, typically <1ms for small grammars).\n- **Runtime performance**: Slower than PEGTL/Spirit for hot paths (virtual dispatch vs templates), but for a query parser that runs once per invocation, this is irrelevant.\n- **Code size**: Extremely compact. The grammar can be written as a string literal.\n\nExample:\n\n```cpp\npeg::parser parser(R\"(\n  QUERY      <- SECTION*\n  SECTION    <- KEYWORD EXPR / EXPR\n  KEYWORD    <- 'show' / 'only' / 'bold' / 'for' / 'since' / 'until'\n  EXPR       <- OR_EXPR\n  OR_EXPR    <- AND_EXPR ('or' AND_EXPR)*\n  AND_EXPR   <- NOT_EXPR ('and' NOT_EXPR)*\n  NOT_EXPR   <- 'not' NOT_EXPR / PRIMARY\n  PRIMARY    <- '(' EXPR ')' / FIELD_MATCH / PATTERN\n  FIELD_MATCH <- [%@#=] PATTERN ('=' PATTERN)?\n  PATTERN    <- QUOTED / REGEX / WORD\n  QUOTED     <- ['] < [^']* > ['] / [\"] < [^\"]* > [\"]\n  REGEX      <- '/' < [^/]* > '/'\n  WORD       <- < [^ \\t\\n\\r()']+ >\n  %whitespace <- [ \\t]*\n)\");\n```\n\nThis is remarkably concise and readable.\n\n### Compile-Time Cost Comparison (approximate, for a ~15 production grammar)\n\n| Library | Compile Time | Runtime Performance | Error Messages | Lines of Code |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Boost.Spirit X3 | 15-30s | Excellent | Poor | 150-250 |\n| PEGTL | 2-5s | Excellent | Good (configurable) | 200-300 |\n| Lexy | 2-5s | Excellent | Excellent | 200-300 |\n| cpp-peglib | <1s | Good (sufficient) | Decent | 50-80 (grammar only) |\n| Hand-written RD | 0s (it's just C++) | Excellent | Full control | 300-500 |\n\n### Key Takeaway\n\nFor ledger's query parser (run once per invocation, ~15 productions), **compile-time cost matters more than runtime performance**. cpp-peglib or a hand-written recursive descent parser would have the lowest impact on build times. PEGTL is a solid middle ground if you want a parser combinator library with compile-time grammar checking.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Parser Generator Approaches\n\n### re2c for the Lexer\n\n**Repository**: `https://re2c.org/`\n\nre2c generates fast, no-dependency C/C++ lexers from regular expression specifications. It works by converting regex patterns to direct-coded DFAs (no tables, just goto statements).\n\nFor ledger's query lexer, the token types would be:\n\n```\n// re2c specification sketch\nenum TokenKind {\n  TOK_AND, TOK_OR, TOK_NOT,\n  TOK_SHOW, TOK_ONLY, TOK_BOLD, TOK_FOR, TOK_SINCE, TOK_UNTIL,\n  TOK_EXPR,\n  TOK_FIELD_PREFIX,  // @, #, %, =\n  TOK_SINGLE_QUOTED, TOK_DOUBLE_QUOTED, TOK_REGEX,\n  TOK_WORD,\n  TOK_LPAREN, TOK_RPAREN,\n  TOK_EQ,            // for %tag=value\n  TOK_EOF\n};\n\n/*!re2c\n  re2c:define:YYCTYPE = char;\n  re2c:yyfill:enable = 0;\n\n  ws      = [ \\t]+;\n  word    = [^ \\t\\n\\r()'\"/=@#%]+;\n  squot   = ['] [^']* ['];\n  dquot   = [\"] [^\"]* [\"];\n  regex   = \"/\" [^/]* \"/\";\n\n  ws        { goto lex; }\n  \"and\"     { return TOK_AND; }\n  \"or\"      { return TOK_OR; }\n  \"not\"     { return TOK_NOT; }\n  \"show\"    { return TOK_SHOW; }\n  \"only\"    { return TOK_ONLY; }\n  \"bold\"    { return TOK_BOLD; }\n  \"for\"     { return TOK_FOR; }\n  \"since\"   { return TOK_SINCE; }\n  \"until\"   { return TOK_UNTIL; }\n  \"expr\"    { return TOK_EXPR; }\n  [@#%=]    { return TOK_FIELD_PREFIX; }\n  \"(\"       { return TOK_LPAREN; }\n  \")\"       { return TOK_RPAREN; }\n  squot     { return TOK_SINGLE_QUOTED; }\n  dquot     { return TOK_DOUBLE_QUOTED; }\n  regex     { return TOK_REGEX; }\n  word      { return TOK_WORD; }\n*/\n```\n\n**Trade-offs**:\n- Adds a build dependency (re2c tool must be available at build time, or you check in the generated `.cc`)\n- Generated code is fast but not human-readable\n- The lexer is the easy part; you still need a parser for the grammar\n\n### PEG Generators\n\n**packcc** (`https://github.com/arithy/packcc`): Generates C parsers from PEG grammars. Supports semantic actions in C. The generated code is a single `.c` file with no dependencies. This is the C equivalent of what cpp-peglib does at runtime.\n\n**peg/leg** (`https://peg-leg.github.io/`): Bryan Ford's original PEG parser generator for C. Very simple, well-tested, generates self-contained C code. The grammar file for ledger's query language would be approximately 60-80 lines.\n\n### The Hand-Written Recursive Descent Approach\n\nFor a grammar this small, a hand-written recursive descent parser is the most common choice in production systems. The pattern:\n\n```cpp\n// Simplified sketch of the parser structure\nclass query_parser_t {\n  const char* pos_;\n  token_t current_;\n\n  void advance();\n  bool match(token_kind_t kind);\n  void expect(token_kind_t kind);\n\n  // Grammar productions map 1:1 to methods\n  query_t parse_query() {\n    // QUERY = SECTION*\n    query_t q;\n    while (!at_end()) {\n      q.sections.push_back(parse_section());\n    }\n    return q;\n  }\n\n  section_t parse_section() {\n    // SECTION = KEYWORD EXPR / EXPR\n    if (is_section_keyword(current_)) {\n      auto kw = current_;\n      advance();\n      return {kw, parse_expr()};\n    }\n    return {nullopt, parse_expr()};\n  }\n\n  expr_ptr parse_expr() {\n    // EXPR = AND_EXPR ('or' AND_EXPR)*\n    auto left = parse_and_expr();\n    while (match(TOK_OR)) {\n      auto right = parse_and_expr();\n      left = make_or(std::move(left), std::move(right));\n    }\n    return left;\n  }\n\n  expr_ptr parse_and_expr() {\n    // AND_EXPR = UNARY ('and'? UNARY)*\n    // Note: implicit AND between adjacent terms (no 'and' keyword needed)\n    auto left = parse_unary();\n    while (!at_end() && !peek(TOK_OR) && !peek(TOK_RPAREN)\n           && !is_section_keyword(current_)) {\n      if (match(TOK_AND)) { /* explicit and, consumed */ }\n      auto right = parse_unary();\n      left = make_and(std::move(left), std::move(right));\n    }\n    return left;\n  }\n\n  expr_ptr parse_unary() {\n    // UNARY = 'not' UNARY / PRIMARY\n    if (match(TOK_NOT)) {\n      return make_not(parse_unary());\n    }\n    return parse_primary();\n  }\n\n  expr_ptr parse_primary() {\n    // PRIMARY = '(' EXPR ')' / FIELD_MATCH / PATTERN\n    if (match(TOK_LPAREN)) {\n      auto e = parse_expr();\n      expect(TOK_RPAREN);\n      return e;\n    }\n    if (peek(TOK_FIELD_PREFIX)) {\n      return parse_field_match();\n    }\n    return parse_pattern();\n  }\n  // ... etc\n};\n```\n\nThis is approximately 300-500 lines of C++ with no external dependencies.\n\n### Pratt Parser Variant\n\nFor the boolean expression core, a Pratt parser (top-down operator precedence) is particularly elegant. The idea: assign binding powers to operators and use a single `parse_expr(min_bp)` function:\n\n```cpp\nexpr_ptr parse_expr(int min_bp = 0) {\n  // Handle prefix operators\n  expr_ptr lhs;\n  if (match(TOK_NOT)) {\n    lhs = make_not(parse_expr(PREFIX_BP));\n  } else {\n    lhs = parse_atom();\n  }\n\n  // Handle infix operators\n  while (true) {\n    int bp = infix_binding_power(current_);\n    if (bp < min_bp) break;\n\n    if (match(TOK_OR)) {\n      lhs = make_or(std::move(lhs), parse_expr(bp + 1));\n    } else if (match(TOK_AND) || is_implicit_and()) {\n      lhs = make_and(std::move(lhs), parse_expr(bp + 1));\n    } else {\n      break;\n    }\n  }\n  return lhs;\n}\n```\n\nWhere binding powers are: `OR = 1`, `AND = 3`, `NOT (prefix) = 5`. This is the pattern used by SQLite FTS5 and many expression parsers. The entire boolean expression parser fits in ~40 lines.\n\nReference for the Pratt parsing technique: Matklad's excellent blog post \"Simple but Powerful Pratt Parsing\" at `https://matklad.github.io/2020/04/13/simple-but-powerful-pratt-parsing.html` (with Rust examples that translate directly to C++).\n\n### Trade-off Summary\n\n| Approach | Build Dependency | Compile Time Impact | Maintainability | Error Messages | Lines |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| re2c + hand-written parser | re2c tool | Minimal | High | Full control | ~400-600 |\n| PEG generator (packcc) | packcc tool | Minimal (generated C) | Medium | Limited | ~80 grammar + generated |\n| cpp-peglib (runtime PEG) | Header-only | <1s | High | Decent | ~80 grammar + ~100 actions |\n| PEGTL | Header-only | 2-5s | High | Good | ~250 |\n| Hand-written RD | None | 0 | Highest | Full control | ~400-500 |\n| Boost.Spirit X3 | Boost (already present) | 15-30s | Medium | Poor | ~200 |\n\n---\n\n## Recommendation\n\nGiven ledger's specific constraints:\n\n1. **Boost is already a dependency**, but Spirit's compile-time cost is significant and the project already has complex build configurations.\n\n2. **The grammar is small** (~15 productions). This is firmly in \"hand-written parser\" territory.\n\n3. **Error messages matter** for a user-facing query language. Hand-written parsers give full control; generated parsers often produce cryptic errors.\n\n4. **The section keyword feature** (`show`, `only`, `for`, etc.) is unusual -- it partitions the query into sub-predicates that apply to different phases of processing. This is a top-level structural concern that is easiest to handle in a hand-written parser where you have full control over the parse flow.\n\n**The recommended approach** is a **hand-written recursive descent parser with a Pratt parser core** for boolean expressions, paired with either:\n\n- A hand-written lexer (simplest, no dependencies, ~100 lines for the token types involved), or\n- A re2c-generated lexer if you want the lexer to be rigorously correct and fast (useful if patterns/regexes have tricky escaping rules).\n\nThe architecture would be:\n\n```\nquery_lexer_t  (hand-written or re2c, ~100-150 lines)\n    |\n    v\nquery_parser_t (recursive descent + Pratt, ~300-400 lines)\n    |\n    v\nquery_t AST    (section keywords -> sub-predicates,\n                boolean tree of field matchers and patterns)\n```\n\nThis is the same pattern used by SQLite FTS5, Lucene's SimpleQueryParser, and (in spirit) hledger's Query.hs -- all proven in production at scale.\n\nIf a parser combinator library is preferred over hand-writing, **PEGTL** is the best fit: it is mature (10+ years), header-only, C++17, well-documented, and its compile-time cost is acceptable. **cpp-peglib** is the best fit if you want to minimize compile-time impact to near zero and do not mind runtime grammar compilation.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>7560</total_tokens><tool_uses>4</tool_uses><duration_ms>130466</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/a316bcdd1bc6ae1eb.output",
