          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a683********b947</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********AxXF</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/a683d26bd9f2fb947.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Performance and efficiency review\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have a complete picture of the code. Here is the full performance review.\n\n---\n\n## Performance Review: `query.h` / `query.cc`\n\n### Context: the performance budget\n\nThe query parser runs exactly once per `ledger` invocation, against a handful of tokens (typically 1-10 command-line words). **None of these issues are in a hot loop over journal transactions.** The predicate produced by the parser is evaluated once per posting at report time, and the parser itself contributes negligibly to wall-clock time for any realistic workload. This framing governs the priority assignments below.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 1: `unbalanced_braces` called on every `)` character inside an `expr` identifier -- potentially O(n²) [HIGH confidence: 90]\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.cc` lines 69-79 and 225-227.\n\nThe identifier accumulation loop in `next_token` calls `unbalanced_braces(ident)` each time it encounters a `)` character while in non-expr context:\n\n```cpp\ncase ')':\n    if (unbalanced_braces(ident))\n        consume_next = true;\n```\n\n`unbalanced_braces` rescans the entire `ident` string from the beginning. If an expr argument contains n closing parens, the total work is `O(1 + 2 + ... + n) = O(n²)`. For a normal query like `expr (foo and (bar or baz))`, n=2 so this is irrelevant. For a pathologically nested expression passed as an expr argument (imagine an automated-transaction condition with deep nesting), n could be 50-100, making this O(2500-10000) character comparisons instead of O(n).\n\n**Expected impact:** Negligible in production (typical n is < 5). However the fix is trivially O(1) and also clarifies intent, which matters for the rewrite.\n\n**Fix:** Track the paren balance as a running counter alongside `ident`, incremented on `(` and decremented on `)`. Test `balance < 0` for \"unbalanced braces\" instead of rescanning. The `unbalanced_braces` function can then be deleted entirely.\n\n```cpp\nint paren_depth = 0;\nfor (; arg_i != arg_end; ++arg_i) {\n    switch (*arg_i) {\n    case '(':\n        ++paren_depth;\n        ident.push_back(*arg_i);\n        break;\n    case ')':\n        if (paren_depth == 0 && !consume_next && tok_context == token_t::TOK_EXPR)\n            goto test_ident;\n        if (paren_depth == 0)\n            consume_next = true;\n        --paren_depth;\n        ident.push_back(*arg_i);\n        break;\n    // ... rest unchanged\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Finding 2: `token_t` is copied excessively -- the cache, peek, and push interfaces all copy [MEDIUM confidence: 85]\n\n**Location:** `query.h` lines 335-343; `query.cc` lines 87-89, 141.\n\n`token_t` contains an `optional<string>`, which means every copy copies the heap-allocated string buffer. This happens at least five times per token in the recursive-descent parser:\n\n1. `next_token` returns by value (copy out of function).\n2. `peek_token` stores into `token_cache` then returns a second copy.\n3. The caller of `peek_token` receives a third copy.\n4. `push_token` takes `const token_t&` and assigns into `token_cache` (copy).\n5. Inside `next_token`, the cache-hit path copies `token_cache` into a local `tok` before clearing it (lines 87-88).\n\nFor keyword tokens (no `value`), `optional<string>` is nullopt and there is no heap copy, only a trivial struct copy. For TERM tokens, each copy clones the pattern string.\n\n**Expected impact:** For a 5-word query with 2 TERM tokens, this is perhaps 10 small string copies. SSO (small-string optimization) will eliminate heap allocation for terms under ~15 bytes (typical account patterns), but longer patterns (`@\"Some Long Payee Name\"`) will each allocate. Probably 200-500 ns of overhead in total -- invisible.\n\n**Fix for the rewrite:** Change `peek_token` to return `const token_t&` (a reference into the cache), and change `push_token` to accept `token_t&&`. The cache-hit path in `next_token` should `std::move` out of `token_cache`:\n\n```cpp\n// In next_token:\nif (token_cache.kind != token_t::UNKNOWN) {\n    token_t tok = std::move(token_cache);\n    token_cache = token_t();   // reset to UNKNOWN\n    return tok;                // NRVO or move, not copy\n}\n\n// peek_token returns a reference:\nconst token_t& peek_token(token_t::kind_t tok_context = token_t::UNKNOWN) {\n    if (token_cache.kind == token_t::UNKNOWN)\n        token_cache = next_token(tok_context);\n    return token_cache;\n}\n\n// push_token accepts by value (caller can move or copy):\nvoid push_token(token_t tok) {\n    assert(token_cache.kind == token_t::UNKNOWN);\n    token_cache = std::move(tok);\n}\n```\n\nAlso add a move constructor and move-assignment operator to `token_t`. The copy constructor and `operator=` are manually defined today (lines 179-190 of `query.h`) but no move operations are declared, which suppresses the compiler-generated moves.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 3: `ident` string built by per-character `push_back` without pre-allocation [LOW confidence: 80]\n\n**Location:** `query.cc` lines 207-246.\n\nThe identifier accumulation loop calls `ident.push_back(*arg_i)` for each character, starting from a default-constructed (empty, zero-capacity) `std::string`. Each push_back beyond SSO capacity triggers a reallocation-and-copy. For typical tokens (< 15 chars), SSO handles this for free. For long `expr` arguments (e.g., `expr \"account =~ /Expenses:Food/ and amount > 100\"`), the string may reallocate 3-4 times.\n\n**Expected impact:** Negligible -- a few realloc calls on a 50-char string once per invocation.\n\n**Fix:** Since `ident_start` already captures the beginning of the identifier within the current arg, and the arg string is stable (owned by `args` in `parser_t`), the entire identifier accumulation could be replaced by a `string_view` pointing directly into the arg's storage for the common case (no whitespace inclusion). This eliminates all allocation in the identifier path. The `string_view` would need to be converted to `string` only when a TERM token's value is stored in `token_t`. This is the highest-leverage `string_view` opportunity in the file.\n\n```cpp\n// Replace the char-by-char loop with:\nstring::const_iterator ident_start = arg_i;\n// ... advance arg_i to end of identifier ...\nstd::string_view ident_sv(ident_start, arg_i);\n// Only allocate when we actually need an owning string:\nif (/* keyword check fails */ ...)\n    return token_t(token_t::TERM, string(ident_sv));\n```\n\nThis only works cleanly if whitespace-inclusion mode (`consume_whitespace`) is not active and no backslash-escapes are present. The rewrite should branch on those conditions.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 4: `ident.substr(0, 4)` allocates a temporary string [LOW confidence: 90]\n\n**Location:** `query.cc` line 259.\n\n```cpp\nif (multiple_args && ident.size() > 4 && ident.substr(0, 4) == \"expr\" && ...)\n```\n\n`std::string::substr` allocates a new heap string. This is a single allocation per `next_token` call when `multiple_args` is true, and only when `ident.size() > 4`. The allocation is completely unnecessary.\n\n**Fix:** Replace with `std::string_view`:\n\n```cpp\nif (multiple_args && ident.size() > 4 &&\n    std::string_view(ident).substr(0, 4) == \"expr\" && ...)\n```\n\nOr more idiomatically:\n\n```cpp\nif (multiple_args && ident.size() > 4 &&\n    ident.compare(0, 4, \"expr\") == 0 && ...)\n```\n\n`std::string::compare` with an offset and length performs no allocation.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 5: `for_string` date accumulation uses repeated `+=` string concatenation [LOW confidence: 85]\n\n**Location:** `query.cc` lines 648-675.\n\n```cpp\nstring for_string;\nif (tok.kind == lexer_t::token_t::TOK_SINCE)\n    for_string = \"since\";\n// ...\nwhile (tok.kind != lexer_t::token_t::END_REACHED) {\n    // ...\n    if (!for_string.empty())\n        for_string += \" \";\n    for_string += *tok.value;\n    // ...\n}\n```\n\nEach `for_string += *tok.value` may trigger a reallocation-and-copy if the string has grown beyond its capacity. For a date string like `\"since 2024/01/01\"` (17 chars) this is at most one reallocation. For a multi-word period like `\"for last 3 months\"` it is 3-4 `+=` calls.\n\n**Expected impact:** Negligible -- maybe 4 small reallocations total.\n\n**Fix for the rewrite:** Pre-reserve or use a local `std::ostringstream`. Better: since the tokens here each correspond to one `argv` argument (the `consume_next_arg` flag forces whole-argument TERM tokens), the entire date string could be constructed by joining at most 3-5 tokens. A `reserve(64)` call before the loop is sufficient.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 6: `predicate_t::print_to_str()` serializes the AST back to a string immediately after building it [MEDIUM confidence: 90]\n\n**Location:** `query.cc` lines 592-593 and 635-636; `exprbase.h` lines 295-299.\n\n```cpp\nquery_map.insert(\n    query_map_t::value_type(QUERY_LIMIT,\n        predicate_t(limiter, what_to_keep).print_to_str()));\n```\n\nThe parser builds an expression tree, immediately serializes it back to a string via `ostringstream`, and discards the tree. Callers then re-parse that string (via `predicate_t(string, ...)`) when they need to evaluate the predicate. This is a round-trip: `string -> AST -> string -> AST` where the middle two steps happen in the query parser with no benefit.\n\n**Expected impact:** The extra AST walk and `ostringstream` are negligible in isolation (< 1 µs). But the deeper issue is that callers must re-parse the serialized string, which means `expr_t`'s full parser runs a second time for each query section. If the `query_map_t` instead stored `predicate_t` objects (owning their ASTs), both the serialization and the re-parse would be eliminated.\n\n**Fix for the rewrite:** Change `query_map_t` from `map<kind_t, string>` to `map<kind_t, predicate_t>`. The `get_query()` accessor that returns a `string` can be kept for backward compatibility by calling `print_to_str()` lazily (or dropped if all callers can accept a `predicate_t` directly). This is an architectural change but it's the right direction: the rewrite is the time to make it.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 7: Token constructor copy-initializes `optional<string>` from a const-ref [LOW confidence: 80]\n\n**Location:** `query.h` line 175-178.\n\n```cpp\nexplicit token_t(kind_t _kind = UNKNOWN, const optional<string>& _value = none)\n    : kind(_kind), value(_value) { ... }\n```\n\nThe constructor always copies `_value`. At each call site that passes a freshly constructed `string` (e.g., line 133: `return token_t(token_t::TERM, pat)`, line 141: `return token_t(token_t::TERM, string(arg_i, arg_end))`), there is one extra copy that could be a move. At SSO sizes this is free, but for larger patterns it causes an unnecessary allocation.\n\n**Fix:** Add an overload (or use a forwarding constructor):\n\n```cpp\nexplicit token_t(kind_t _kind, optional<string> _value)\n    : kind(_kind), value(std::move(_value)) { ... }\n```\n\nAll existing call sites pass rvalues (`pat`, `string(...)`, `ident`) so they will bind to the by-value overload and the move will eliminate the copy.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 8: `query.h` includes `predicate.h` which pulls in the full expression/value/commodity/annotate chain [MEDIUM confidence: 85]\n\n**Location:** `query.h` line 81.\n\n```\nquery.h -> predicate.h -> expr.h + commodity.h + annotate.h\n         -> expr.h -> exprbase.h + value.h\n         -> value.h -> balance.h -> amount.h\n```\n\nEvery translation unit that includes `query.h` (and there are many -- any file that handles command-line options or report configuration) pays this entire include chain at compile time. The chain reaches `balance.h -> amount.h`, which are among the heaviest headers in the codebase (they include Boost.Multiprecision and related machinery).\n\n**Expected impact:** This is the highest-impact item for compile-time performance. Each TU that includes `query.h` compiles significantly more than it would if `query.h` used forward declarations.\n\n**Fix for the rewrite:** `query.h` itself does not need to expose `predicate_t` or `expr_t` in its public interface. The `parse_args()` return type `expr_t::ptr_op_t` and the `parser_t` members could be moved to `query.cc` (they are already `protected`/`private`). The public interface of `query_t` only requires:\n- `query_map_t` (which is `map<kind_t, string>` -- no heavy deps)\n- `keep_details_t` (from `annotate.h`)\n- `value_t::sequence_t` for the constructor\n\nWith forward declarations for `keep_details_t` and opaque handling of the `parser` member (`optional<parser_t>` where `parser_t` is forward-declared), `query.h` could be reduced to include only `<map>`, `<string>`, and a lightweight types header. The full expression machinery would be confined to `query.cc`.\n\n---\n\n### Summary table (prioritized for rewrite impact)\n\n| # | Issue | Category | Impact | Effort |\n|---|-------|----------|--------|--------|\n| 8 | Heavy include chain via `predicate.h` | Compile time | Medium (every TU recompiles) | Medium |\n| 6 | AST-to-string-to-AST round-trip in query_map | Unnecessary work | Medium (eliminates two parse passes) | Medium |\n| 1 | `unbalanced_braces` O(n²) rescans | Algorithmic | Low (n < 10 in practice) | Trivial |\n| 2 | `token_t` copied instead of moved | Allocation | Low (SSO covers most cases) | Low |\n| 4 | `substr(0,4)` allocates temporary | Allocation | Negligible | Trivial |\n| 3 | `ident` built char-by-char; `string_view` viable | Allocation | Negligible | Low |\n| 5 | `for_string +=` repeated concatenation | Allocation | Negligible | Trivial |\n| 7 | Token constructor copies `optional<string>` | Allocation | Negligible | Trivial |\n\n**Recommendations for the rewrite, in order:**\n\n1. **Do Finding 8 first** (decouple `query.h` from the expression engine). This is the only change with meaningful compile-time impact and it simplifies the public API.\n2. **Do Finding 6** (store `predicate_t` in the map, not strings). This eliminates a structural inefficiency that currently costs two full parse passes per query section.\n3. **Do Findings 1, 2, 4, 7 together** as a single mechanical pass -- they are all trivial and make the code cleaner regardless of performance.\n4. **Skip Findings 3 and 5** unless profiling shows they matter. The `string_view` refactor for identifier accumulation adds complexity for zero measurable benefit given that the parser runs once per invocation against < 20 tokens.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>47011</total_tokens><tool_uses>15</tool_uses><duration_ms>113408</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/a683d26bd9f2fb947.output",
