          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>abdc********06f8</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********tyGJ</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/abdc9afe71a6406f8.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"UX analysis of query language\" completed</summary>\n<result>Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the query syntax, error messages, the query precommand, and the parser internals. Let me compile the analysis.\n\n---\n\n## UX Analysis of the Ledger Query Parser\n\n### 1. Error Message Quality\n\nThe error messages in `coverage-query-errors.test` and `coverage-query-errors2.test` reveal several problems.\n\n**What the current errors provide:**\n- A short description of what went wrong: `\"payee operator not followed by argument\"`, `\"not operator not followed by argument\"`, `\"Missing ')'\"`, `\"Metadata equality operator not followed by term\"`\n\n**What the current errors lack:**\n- **No position information.** The user gets `Error: payee operator not followed by argument` but is not told *where* in the query the problem occurred. For a query like `@Grocery and @`, the message does not indicate that it was the second `@` that failed.\n- **No echo of the input.** The failing query is never shown back to the user with a caret or underline pointing at the offending position.\n- **No suggestions.** A trailing `@` could prompt: \"Did you mean `@SomePayee`?\" or at least \"The `@` operator must be followed by a payee pattern.\"\n- **Inconsistent phrasing.** The `expected(char)` function produces `\"Missing '%1%'\"` (e.g., `Missing ')'`), while operator errors produce `\"%1% operator not followed by argument\"`. The former uses the word \"missing,\" the latter says \"not followed by.\" The word \"argument\" is programmer jargon -- \"pattern\" or \"search term\" would be clearer to an accounting user.\n- **No distinction between lexer and parser errors.** `\"%tag=\"` produces `\"meta operator not followed by argument\"` (the `=` is lexed as TOK_EQ, then the parser fails to find a TERM after it), while `\"%tag=&\"` produces `\"Metadata equality operator not followed by term\"`. These are different phases of failure, but the user has no way to understand that distinction.\n\n**Actionable recommendations for the rewrite:**\n- Add source position tracking (argument index + character offset) to every error.\n- Echo the original query with a caret indicating the error location, e.g.:\n  ```\n  Error: Expected a payee pattern after '@'\n    ledger reg @Grocery and @\n                             ^\n  ```\n- Use consistent, user-facing terminology: \"pattern\" instead of \"argument\" or \"term.\"\n- Where feasible, show what valid syntax looks like: `\"Expected a tag name after '%', e.g. %Category\"`.\n\n### 2. Consistency Analysis of Shorthand Operators\n\n**The operator table:**\n\n| Prefix | Keyword synonyms | Matches | Notes |\n|--------|-----------------|---------|-------|\n| `@` | `payee`, `desc` | payee field | Two keyword aliases for one concept |\n| `#` | `code` | transaction code | Clean, one-to-one |\n| `=` | `note` | note field | Overloaded (see below) |\n| `%` | `meta`, `tag`, `data` | metadata tags | Three keyword aliases for one concept |\n| `!` | `not` | logical NOT | Clean |\n| `&` | `and` | logical AND | Clean |\n| `\\|` | `or` | logical OR | Clean |\n\n**Identified inconsistencies:**\n\n**(a) `=` is overloaded.** When `=` appears at the start of an argument, it means \"note match\" (`=food` becomes `note =~ /food/`). But when `=` appears after a `%tag` expression, it means \"equality comparison\" (`%Category=food` becomes `has_tag(/Category/, /food/)`). This dual meaning is context-sensitive. A user encountering `%tag=value` for the first time might reasonably wonder why `=` works differently there than in `=note`. The code at line 192-198 of `query.cc` explicitly checks whether `=` is at the start of the argument string to decide which token to produce. This position-sensitivity is fragile and surprising.\n\n**(b) Three synonyms for metadata.** `meta`, `tag`, and `data` all map to `TOK_META`. While flexibility is nice, this creates confusion: \"Which is canonical?\" The documentation challenge is real -- should a tutorial say `%`, `meta`, `tag`, or `data`? Similarly, `payee` and `desc` are both valid. Having canonical forms would help discoverability.\n\n**(c) No prefix shorthand for `code`.** `#` exists for code, and `@` for payee, but there is no single-character shorthand for `account` (the default context) or `expr`. This is actually fine -- account being the default is the right choice -- but it means the shorthand system is inherently incomplete, which can confuse users who expect symmetry.\n\n**(d) `%tag` matches both tag existence and `:tag:` style tags.** The `%food` query matches both `; :food:` tags and `; food: value` metadata. This is intentional (it calls `has_tag()`) but the difference between tag existence (`%food`) and tag value matching (`%food=bar`) is not obvious from the syntax.\n\n**(e) Implicit OR at the top level.** Multiple bare terms at the top level are implicitly OR-ed: `food groceries` means `account =~ /food/ | account =~ /groceries/`. But after `and`, terms require explicit conjunction: `food and groceries` means `account =~ /food/ & account =~ /groceries/`. The implicit OR is convenient but can surprise users who expect `food groceries` to mean `food AND groceries` (since both words describe what they want to find).\n\n### 3. The `query` Precommand\n\nThe `query` precommand output (seen in `cov6-report-query-precommand.test` and `coverage-wave3-precommands.test`) shows:\n\n```\n--- Input arguments ---\n(\"Expenses\")\n\n--- Context is first posting of the following transaction ---\n2004/05/27 Book Store\n    ...\n\n--- Input expression ---\n(account =~ /Expenses/)\n\n--- Text as parsed ---\n(account =~ /Expenses/)\n\n--- Expression tree ---\n0xXXXX O_MATCH (1)\n0xXXXX IDENT: account (1)\n0xXXXX VALUE: /Expenses/ (1)\n\n--- Compiled tree ---\n0xXXXX O_MATCH (1)\n0xXXXX IDENT: account (1)\n0xXXXX FUNCTION (1)\n0xXXXX VALUE: /Expenses/ (1)\n\n--- Calculated value ---\ntrue\n```\n\n**What works well:**\n- The \"Input expression\" and \"Text as parsed\" sections are extremely useful -- they show the user exactly what their shorthand expanded to: `Expenses` becomes `(account =~ /Expenses/)`. This is the single most useful debugging feature.\n- The \"Calculated value\" against the sample context provides immediate feedback.\n\n**What could be improved:**\n- **The expression tree and compiled tree are developer artifacts.** Memory addresses (`0xXXXX`), op-code names like `O_MATCH`, `O_AND`, `IDENT`, `FUNCTION`, and the `(1)` reference counts are meaningless to users. These should either be hidden by default (shown with `--verbose` or `--debug`) or reformatted into something human-readable.\n- **The sample transaction is hardcoded.** The context is always `2004/05/27 Book Store` -- not from the user's actual data. This means the \"Calculated value\" (true/false) may not match the user's mental model. It would be far more useful to evaluate against the first matching posting from the user's own journal.\n- **No per-section breakdown.** For a query like `Expenses for 2024 show Food`, the output should clearly show: \"LIMIT: `account =~ /Expenses/`\", \"FOR: `2024`\", \"SHOW: `account =~ /Food/`\". Currently the `query` precommand shows the LIMIT section only and does not display the period or display predicates.\n- **The `args` precommand is redundant.** Both `query` and `args` exist and produce nearly identical output. The difference is unclear to users.\n\n**Actionable recommendations:**\n- Make the \"Input expression\" / \"Text as parsed\" output the primary (and possibly only) output of `query`. This is what users actually need.\n- Show all sections: LIMIT, SHOW, ONLY, BOLD, FOR.\n- Drop the raw tree dumps from default output; make them available via `--debug` flags.\n- Evaluate against the user's actual journal data, not a hardcoded sample.\n\n### 4. Discoverability\n\n**How would a new user learn the query syntax?**\n\nThe grammar is reasonably regular but has enough special cases that discovery by experimentation is unreliable:\n\n- **Bare words default to account matching.** This is intuitive: `ledger bal food` matches accounts containing \"food\". Most users will discover this naturally.\n- **The `@`, `#`, `%`, `=` prefixes are not self-documenting.** There is no mnemonic connection between `@` and payee (unlike, say, email where `@` means \"at\"). A user would need to find documentation or use `ledger query` to experiment.\n- **Keywords are verbose but discoverable.** `payee`, `code`, `note`, `meta` are English words that make sense. A user could guess `payee Grocery` works. But the aliases (`desc` for payee, `data`/`tag` for meta) fragment the search space: a user reading an example with `desc` might not know it is the same as `payee`.\n- **Section keywords are natural language.** `show`, `only`, `bold`, `for`, `since`, `until` read like English: `ledger reg for 2024 show Expenses`. This is a strong UX feature.\n- **The `expr` escape hatch breaks the abstraction.** Going from `@Grocery` to `expr 'amount > 100'` is a huge cognitive jump -- the user suddenly needs to know the expression language, field names, and quoting rules. There is no gradual path from the query shorthand to full expressions.\n\n**The grammar is NOT regular enough to explain in one sentence.** It requires explaining:\n1. Default context (bare words = account)\n2. Prefix operators (`@`, `#`, `%`, `=`)\n3. Keyword operators (`payee`, `code`, `note`, `meta`, `expr`)\n4. Boolean connectives (`and`/`&`, `or`/`|`, `not`/`!`)\n5. Section keywords (`show`, `only`, `bold`, `for`, `since`, `until`)\n6. Implicit OR between top-level terms\n7. The `=` overloading in `%tag=value`\n8. Quoting rules (single quotes, double quotes, `/regex/`)\n\n**Actionable recommendations:**\n- Provide a `ledger help query` or `ledger query --help` that prints a concise syntax reference.\n- Establish canonical forms: recommend `@` over `payee`/`desc`, `%` over `meta`/`tag`/`data`, etc. (or vice versa), and document the alternatives as aliases.\n- Consider a gradual syntax for amount/date filtering that does not require the `expr` escape hatch, e.g., `amount > 100` directly in query syntax.\n\n### 5. Edge Cases That Surprise Users\n\n**(a) Implicit OR between bare terms.**\n`ledger reg food groceries` means `account =~ /food/ OR account =~ /groceries/`. Many users expect AND. The `args` precommand confirms this -- the args test shows `(\"Expenses\", \"and\", \"Food\")` as three separate arguments producing an AND, but `(\"Expenses\", \"Food\")` would produce OR. This is a well-known source of confusion.\n\n**(b) `=` as note vs. `=` as equality in `%tag=value`.**\nIn multi-arg mode, `=foo` at the start of an argument means \"note contains foo.\" But `%tag=foo` inside the same argument means \"metadata tag equals foo.\" If a user writes `%tag =foo`, the space causes the `=` to be at the start of a new argument, so it becomes a note match rather than tag equality. The test `coverage-query-meta-error.test` shows that `\"%tag=\"` (with nothing after the `=`) errors as \"meta operator not followed by argument\" -- not \"equality operator not followed by value.\" The error does not help the user understand what went wrong.\n\n**(c) Backslash escaping is minimal and inconsistent.**\nThe test `coverage-query-escape.test` shows `'@\\&B'` -- the backslash before `&` prevents `&` from being treated as AND. But the mechanism is ad-hoc: the `consume_next` flag is set, which causes the *next* character to be included literally. This means `\\` only escapes the immediately following character within the identifier accumulation phase. It does not work in all contexts (e.g., you cannot es