rdered commits.**\n\n### 2. Incremental Commit Sequence (Not Big-Bang)\n\nA big-bang replacement is too risky given the 89+ regression test files, 112 unit tests, and 4 external call sites. Instead, use a series of 5-7 commits, each independently compilable and test-passing.\n\n**Milestone 1: Preparatory refactors (no behavior change)**\n\nCommit 1a: **Extract keyword lookup into a helper function.**\n- The keyword-matching chain in `next_token()` (lines 266-303 of `query.cc`) is a long `if/else if` chain. Extract it into a private `match_keyword(const string&) -> optional<token_t::kind_t>` method. This is a pure refactor.\n- Also extract the identifier accumulation loop (lines 207-253) into a `scan_identifier()` helper.\n- Verification: build + run unit tests (`ctest -R expr`) + run query regression tests (`ctest -R coverage-query`).\n\nCommit 1b: **Extract the \"comparison expression detection\" logic into a helper.**\n- The block at lines 400-431 in `parse_query_term` that detects `>=[`, `<[` patterns is complex. Extract it into `try_parse_as_comparison(const string& term, ...) -> expr_t::ptr_op_t`.\n- Verification: same as 1a.\n\nCommit 1c: **Extract the implicit-OR accumulation pattern into a helper.**\n- The identical pattern in `parse_query_expr` appears three times (lines 577-586, 623-632, and the show/only/bold block). Extract into `accumulate_or_exprs(tok_context) -> expr_t::ptr_op_t`.\n- Verification: same as above.\n\n**Milestone 2: Lexer restructuring**\n\nCommit 2a: **Restructure `next_token()` to eliminate `goto resume` and `goto test_ident`.**\n- Replace the `resume:` label with a proper loop (`while (true) { ... if (not whitespace) break; ... }`).\n- Replace the `goto test_ident` exits from the identifier accumulation loop with early returns or a flag variable.\n- This is the highest-risk lexer change. The `goto` targets interact with the `consume_next`, `consume_whitespace`, `consume_next_arg`, and `multiple_args` flags in subtle ways.\n- Verification: **full ctest suite** -- this change affects tokenization of every query.\n\nCommit 2b: **Refactor the `=` dual-meaning logic.**\n- Currently, `=` at the start of an argument produces `TOK_NOTE`; elsewhere it produces `TOK_EQ`. This check (`arg_i == (*begin).as_string().begin()`) depends on the argument iterator state. Encapsulate this into a `is_at_arg_start()` predicate method.\n- Verification: build + `ctest -R coverage-query-eq` + `ctest -R coverage-query-meta-eq` + `ctest -R coverage-query-note`.\n\n**Milestone 3: Parser restructuring**\n\nCommit 3a: **Restructure `parse_query_expr` section-keyword handling.**\n- The `for`/`since`/`until` block (lines 643-681) directly manipulates lexer internals (`lexer.consume_next_arg`, `lexer.token_cache`, `lexer.arg_i`, `lexer.prev_arg_i`). This is the messiest parser-lexer coupling.\n- Option A: Expose a proper lexer method like `consume_raw_arg() -> string` that encapsulates the \"consume next argument as raw text\" pattern, and `rewind_to_previous_arg()` for the keyword break.\n- Option B: Introduce a `scan_date_range_args()` method on the parser that encapsulates the entire for/since/until scanning loop.\n- Recommend Option B: it keeps the messy lexer interaction in one clearly-documented place.\n- Verification: `ctest -R coverage-query-for` + `ctest -R coverage-query-since` + `ctest -R coverage-query-until` + the full query regression suite.\n\nCommit 3b: **Eliminate `goto done` in `parse_query_expr`.**\n- Replace with a `bool done = false` loop variable or by restructuring the switch into a function.\n- Verification: full query test suite.\n\n**Milestone 4: Final cleanup**\n\nCommit 4: **Add/update documentation, remove dead code paths, final formatting pass.**\n- Ensure `.clang-format` compliance.\n- Verify all NOLINT comments are still necessary or remove them.\n- Verification: full ctest suite.\n\n### 3. Testing Strategy at Each Step\n\n| Step | Test Subset | Time Estimate | Rationale |\n|------|------------|---------------|-----------|\n| Each preparatory refactor (1a-1c) | `ctest -R \"expr\\|coverage-query\"` (~200 tests) | ~30s | Pure refactors, only query code touched |\n| Lexer restructuring (2a) | **Full `ctest`** (~4000+ tests) | ~3-5 min | Tokenization change affects all query parsing; need to catch any edge case across the entire suite |\n| `=` dual-meaning (2b) | `ctest -R \"coverage-query-eq\\|coverage-query-note\\|coverage-query-meta\"` (~15 tests) + `ctest -R \"textual\\|xact\"` for automated transactions | ~30s | Focused on the `=` semantics |\n| for/since/until refactor (3a) | `ctest -R \"coverage-query-for\\|coverage-query-since\\|coverage-query-until\\|coverage-query-bold\"` (~15 tests) + full query suite | ~1 min | Date scanning is subtle; also tests show/bold keyword interleaving |\n| goto elimination (3b) | Full query regression + unit tests | ~1 min | Structural change to control flow |\n| Final cleanup (4) | **Full `ctest`** | ~3-5 min | Final validation |\n\n**Critical: before starting, establish the baseline.** Build the project and run `ctest` to confirm all tests pass on the current code. Save the output as a reference.\n\n### 4. Risk Mitigation\n\n**Risk 1: `expr` keyword's consume-next-arg behavior**\n- **What's tricky**: The `expr` keyword has two code paths. When `multiple_args=true` and the word \"expr\" appears as a prefix of a larger string (e.g., `\"expr amount>0\"` as a single argument), lines 259-263 detect it, rewind `arg_i`, and set `consume_next_arg`. When \"expr\" is a standalone keyword (line 298-301), it simply sets `consume_next_arg` for the next `next_token()` call.\n- **Mitigation**: Do not change the `consume_next_arg` mechanism itself in the early commits. Extract the keyword lookup (Commit 1a) but keep the `expr` special case exactly where it is. Only clean up the `expr` handling in a later commit after the keyword lookup refactor is validated.\n- **Test coverage**: `coverage-query-expr.test`, `coverage-query-expr-inline.test`, `coverage-query-expr-keyword.test`, `cov6-query-expr.test`, plus unit tests `testPredicateTokenizer8` through `testPredicateTokenizer10`.\n\n**Risk 2: `for`/`since`/`until` date scanning with keyword rewind**\n- **What's tricky**: The parser loop (lines 655-676) forces the lexer into \"consume entire argument as TERM\" mode (`consume_next_arg = true`), then manually checks if the consumed term is a section keyword. If it is, the parser clears the token cache, rewinds `arg_i` to `prev_arg_i`, and breaks. This is the only place in the codebase that rewinds the lexer.\n- **Mitigation**: In Commit 3a, wrap this entire interaction in a single `scan_date_range_args()` method. Write a thorough comment explaining the rewind mechanism. Do NOT try to eliminate the rewind -- it is load-bearing behavior that would require redesigning how the lexer and parser interact for date ranges.\n- **Test coverage**: `coverage-query-for-break.test`, `coverage-query-for-combined.test`, `coverage-query-for-show.test`, `coverage-query-for-since-until.test`, `coverage-query-since-date.test`, `coverage-query-since-for.test`, `coverage-query-since-until.test`.\n\n**Risk 3: `=` dual meaning**\n- **What's tricky**: `=` at the start of an argument is `TOK_NOTE` (note matching), but `=` elsewhere is `TOK_EQ` (metadata value comparison). The check `arg_i == (*begin).as_string().begin()` compares character iterators -- it works because `arg_i` is reset to the start of each new argument string when `begin` advances.\n- **Mitigation**: Extract into a named predicate (`is_at_arg_start()`) for clarity but do NOT change the semantics. Test both meanings explicitly.\n- **Test coverage**: `coverage-query-eq-note.test`, `coverage-query-meta-eq.test`, `cov6-query-meta-eq.test`, plus unit test `testPredicateTokenizer6`.\n\n**Risk 4: Implicit OR at top level**\n- **What's tricky**: When two bare terms appear consecutively without an explicit `and`/`or`, they are implicitly OR-ed. This happens because `parse_query_expr` calls `parse_or_expr` in a loop and OR-joins the results. But `parse_or_expr -> parse_and_expr -> parse_unary_expr -> parse_query_term` returns `nullptr` when it hits a section keyword (show/only/bold/for/since/until) or END_REACHED, which terminates the loop.\n- **Mitigation**: When extracting the `accumulate_or_exprs` helper (Commit 1c), ensure the termination condition is identical. Write a regression test comment explaining the implicit-OR semantics.\n- **Test coverage**: `coverage-query-payee-or.test`, `coverage-query-complex-or.test`, `coverage-query-pipe-or.test`, `cov2-query-ops.test`.\n\n**Risk 5: `multiple_args` flag's deep effects on tokenization**\n- **What's tricky**: When `multiple_args=false` (single string input, used by `textual_xacts.cc` for automated transactions), whitespace breaks identifiers instead of being included in them (line 219). This fundamentally changes how tokens like `\"food and bar\"` are lexed. Additionally, `consume_next_arg` is only activated when `multiple_args=true` (line 139).\n- **Mitigation**: Never change the `multiple_args` conditional branches without running both the multi-arg unit tests (testPredicateTokenizer1/3/4/5 etc.) AND the single-arg unit tests (testPredicateTokenizer2/5/16). Also run `ctest -R textual` to exercise the automated transaction path.\n- **Test coverage**: Unit tests with `multiple_args=false`: testPredicateTokenizer2, testPredicateTokenizer5, testPredicateTokenizer8, testPredicateTokenizer16. End-to-end: `coverage-xact-query-pred.test`.\n\n### 5. Rollback Plan\n\n**Layer 1: Git branch isolation.**\nAll work is on the `johnw/query-parser` branch. If the rewrite introduces subtle bugs post-merge, `git revert` the merge commit on `main` to restore the previous `query.h` and `query.cc` atomically.\n\n**Layer 2: Incremental commits enable surgical rollback.**\nBecause each commit is independently valid, a subtle bug can be bisected to the exact commit that introduced it (`git bisect` with `ctest` as the test command). Then only that commit needs to be reverted or fixed.\n\n**Layer 3: Preserve the old code as a reference.**\nBefore starting, create a tag `pre-query-rewrite` on the current HEAD. This provides a permanent reference point for diffing.\n\n**Layer 4: Semantic equivalence testing.**\nFor the most paranoid validation, before merging, run a differential test:\n1. Build the old code and the new code side by side (two worktrees).\n2. Run every `.test` file through both binaries and diff the outputs.\n3. Any difference is a bug in the rewrite.\n\nThis can be scripted:\n```bash\nfor f in test/regress/coverage-query-*.test test/regress/cov*-query-*.test; do\n  diff <(python3 test/RegressTests.py --ledger ./old-build/ledger --sourcepath . \"$f\" 2>&1) \\\n       <(python3 test/RegressTests.py --ledger ./new-build/ledger --sourcepath . \"$f\" 2>&1) \\\n    || echo \"MISMATCH: $f\"\ndone\n```\n\n### Summary: Milestone Checklist\n\n| # | Commit | Files Changed | Key Risk | Verification |\n|---|--------|--------------|----------|-------------|\n| 1a | Extract keyword lookup helper | query.cc | Low | Unit + query regression |\n| 1b | Extract comparison detection helper | query.cc | Low | Unit + query regression |\n| 1c | Extract implicit-OR accumulation helper | query.cc | Low | Unit + query regression |\n| 2a | Eliminate goto in next_token() | query.cc | **HIGH** | **Full ctest** |\n| 2b | Encapsulate `=` dual meaning | query.cc | Medium | Targeted + query regression |\n| 3a | Encapsulate for/since/until scanning | query.cc | **HIGH** | Targeted + full query suite |\n| 3b | Eliminate goto done in parse_query_expr | query.cc | Medium | Full query suite |\n| 4 | Documentation + cleanup | query.h, query.cc | Low | **Full ctest** |\n\nThe total estimated time for the rewrite itself is moderate -- the code is ~700 lines total. The dominant cost is careful testing at each step. The incremental approach means that at no point are we more than one commit away from a known-good state.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>61579</total_tokens><tool_uses>47</tool_uses><duration_ms>192090</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/af9c6d218edd6be6a.output",
