does it break at \"until\" or \"show\"?)\n  - Backslash at end of argument (the `\\\\` at line 200-202 sets `consume_next` but what if arg_end is reached immediately?)\n\n### 5. Alternative: Targeted Cleanup Instead of Full Rewrite\n\nThe real target should be `next_token()` alone. Here is what a minimal-risk refactor looks like:\n\n1. **Extract `scan_quoted_pattern()`** from lines 106-134. Pure function, no state mutation beyond `arg_i`. Safe to extract.\n\n2. **Extract `scan_identifier()`** from lines 207-254. This is the hairy part, but it is self-contained: it reads from `arg_i` and produces a string plus some side effects on `consume_whitespace`. Making it a method clarifies the contract.\n\n3. **Replace the `resume:` goto** with a `while(true)` loop and `continue`. One-line structural change.\n\n4. **Replace the `test_ident:` goto** with an early-return or extracted function. The three jump sites all mean \"stop accumulating, test what we have.\"\n\n5. **Replace the `done:` goto** with a labeled break or restructured loop.\n\nThese 5 changes would eliminate all gotos, improve readability, and touch only `next_token()`. The parser functions do not need any changes because they are already clean recursive descent.\n\nTotal risk: low. Total effort: a few hours. Total benefit: eliminates all the \"messy\" code.\n\n### 6. The \"Clean Code\" Trap\n\nWhat does \"clean recursive-descent parser\" mean when the parser IS ALREADY recursive descent? Re-read `parse_unary_expr`, `parse_and_expr`, `parse_or_expr`. They are 15-25 lines each, follow the textbook pattern exactly, and have clear documentation. What would a rewrite improve?\n\nThe risk of a full rewrite is that you introduce a new set of idioms, new naming conventions, a new token flow model, and then you have to verify that every single behavior is preserved. You have 80+ test files, but as I argued above, they are end-to-end and may not catch subtle semantic shifts.\n\nThe \"Second System Effect\" (Brooks, *The Mythical Man-Month*) is the tendency to over-design a rewrite. The current code's ugliness is contained. A rewrite spreads risk everywhere.\n\n### 7. Hidden Dependencies\n\n- `predicate_t::print_to_str()` serializes the AST back to a string, and that string is passed to report handlers via `HANDLER(limit_).on(whence, pred)`. If the rewrite produces a semantically equivalent but structurally different AST, `print_to_str()` might produce a different string. The string is then re-parsed by the expression engine. A different string could parse differently or fail. This is an indirect dependency that no test explicitly validates.\n\n- `parse_args()` is called exactly once per `query_t` instance (guarded by `if (!parser)`). The return value (the limit expression tree) is used directly only in `report.cc` lines 395-403, where it is checked for `O_MATCH` to detect xact-level predicates. The rewrite must preserve the exact tree structure for this check, not just semantic equivalence.\n\n### Verdict\n\nThe plan confuses two different problems: (a) `next_token()` is hard to read, and (b) the parser needs a rewrite. Problem (a) is real but small -- 226 lines with 4 gotos in one function. Problem (b) is false -- the parser is already clean. A full rewrite to solve problem (a) is like demolishing a house because one room needs painting.\n\nMy recommendation: do the targeted cleanup of `next_token()` described in section 5. Leave the parser functions untouched. Add a formal grammar comment at the top of the file (you can do this without changing any code). And invest the time you save in writing the missing edge-case tests identified in section 4, which will provide far more value than a structural rewrite.</result>\n<usage><total_tokens>46326</total_tokens><tool_uses>28</tool_uses><duration_ms>149800</duration_ms></usage>\n</task-notification>\nFull transcript available at: /private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/a3