imit`       |\n * | `show`            | QUERY_SHOW    | `--display`     |\n * | `only`            | QUERY_ONLY    | `--only`        |\n * | `bold`            | QUERY_BOLD    | `--bold-if`     |\n * | `for`/`since`/`until` | QUERY_FOR | `--period`      |\n *\n * Each predicate is serialized to a string via predicate_t::print_to_str()\n * and stored in the query_map.  The report engine retrieves these strings\n * to configure its filtering pipeline (limit, display, only, bold-if)\n * and date range (period).\n *\n * @subsection arch_example Complete Example\n *\n * @code\n *   Input:   \"food and @grocery show %receipt for 2024\"\n *\n *   Tokens:  TERM(\"food\") TOK_AND TOK_PAYEE TERM(\"grocery\")\n *            TOK_SHOW TOK_META TERM(\"receipt\")\n *            TOK_FOR TERM(\"2024\")\n *\n *   AST:     O_AND\n *            +-- O_MATCH(account, /food/)\n *            +-- O_MATCH(payee, /grocery/)\n *\n *   query_map:\n *     QUERY_LIMIT -> \"(account =~ /food/) & (payee =~ /grocery/)\"\n *     QUERY_SHOW  -> \"has_tag(/receipt/)\"\n *     QUERY_FOR   -> \"2024\"\n * @endcode\n *\n * @subsection arch_ownership Ownership and Lifetime\n *\n * query_t owns the parser_t, which owns the lexer_t and the original\n * argument sequence (value_t).  The lexer holds iterators into the\n * argument strings, so the value_t must outlive the lexer.  The parser\n * stores results in query_map as serialized strings, so the AST nodes\n * are transient and do not need to outlive the parse call.\n *\n * @see predicate_t for the boolean wrapper applied to each parsed expression.\n * @see expr_t::op_t for the AST node types (O_MATCH, O_AND, O_OR, etc.).\n */\n```\n\n---\n\n## Summary\n\nHere is what I produced and the key findings:\n\n**Evaluation**: The existing documentation is accurate and better than most C++ codebases, but has significant gaps around the implicit-OR behavior, the `=` position sensitivity, the comparison expression heuristic, and the date-term rewind mechanism. No misl