          "text": "<task-notification>\n<task-id>a221********b98e</task-id>\n<tool-use-id>tool********ddrr</tool-use-id>\n<output-file>/private/tmp/claude-501/-Users-johnw-src-ledger-query-parser/83b6aaea-84ed-426b-97f1-627cf7268c6c/tasks/a2217abb41206b98e.output</output-file>\n<status>completed</status>\n<summary>Agent \"Security and code safety review\" completed</summary>\n<result>Good — AND and OR chains are iterative (while loops). The only real recursion is through `LPAREN` -> `parse_query_expr` -> `parse_or_expr` -> `parse_and_expr` -> `parse_unary_expr` -> `parse_query_term` -> `LPAREN`. That's 5 stack frames per nesting level. And `not not not` chains go through `parse_unary_expr` -> `parse_query_term` (not recursive into `parse_unary_expr` again, since `parse_query_term` handles `not` by recursing into itself only for field-prefix tokens). Wait — let me re-check: `not` in `parse_unary_expr` calls `parse_query_term`, not `parse_unary_expr`. So `not not not` would be: first `not` consumed by `parse_unary_expr`, then `parse_query_term` is called, which gets `not` as a field context token... no, `TOK_NOT` is not handled in `parse_query_term` — it falls to `default: lexer.push_token(tok); break;` — so the second `not` gets pushed back and the first `not` has no operand, triggering the error. So `not` chains are safe.\n\nFor `((((...` nesting, each `LPAREN` consumed in `parse_query_term` (line 472) calls `parse_query_expr`, which is the full recursion depth. No limit is imposed.\n\nNow I have everything I need. Here is the complete security review:\n\n---\n\n## Security Review: `query.h` / `query.cc`\n\n---\n\n### Finding 1 — CRITICAL: `parser_t` Copy Constructor Leaves Iterators Aliased to Copied-From Object's Storage\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.h`, lines 418–420\n\n```cpp\nparser_t(const parser_t& other) : args(other.args), lexer(other.lexer) {\n```\n\n**What happens.** `args` is a `value_t`. `value_t`'s copy constructor is