iterator` with no initializer. It is only assigned at line 142, inside the branch:\n\n```cpp\nif (multiple_args && consume_next_arg) {\n    ...\n    prev_arg_i = arg_i;\n    arg_i = arg_end;\n```\n\nBut it is unconditionally used at line 665:\n\n```cpp\nlexer.arg_i = lexer.prev_arg_i;\n```\n\nThis use is inside the `for`/`since`/`until` section processing, where `consume_next_arg` is set to `true` before peeking. The first iteration of the loop does trigger the `consume_next_arg` branch and assigns `prev_arg_i`. However, if the argument stream is empty when `consume_next_arg` is first set (i.e., `for` appears as the last token), `peek_token` returns `END_REACHED` immediately, the `while` loop does not execute, and `prev_arg_i` is never written — yet if execution somehow reaches line 665, the iterator is uninitialized. Additionally, a `lexer_t` constructed via the copy constructor copies `prev_arg_i` from `other`, which — before any `consume_next_arg` path fires in `other` — is also uninitialized.\n\n**Recommendation.** Initialize `prev_arg_i` to a known value in the `lexer_t` constructor (e.g., `arg_i` itself). Add an explicit guard (`assert(prev_arg_i != string::const_iterator{})` or a boolean flag) before every use of `prev_arg_i` at line 665.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 3 — HIGH: Assert-Guarded `tok.kind == TERM` Inside `for` Loop Is Reachable with Malicious Input in Release Builds\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.cc`, line 660\n\n```cpp\nassert(tok.kind == lexer_t::token_t::TERM);\n```\n\nInside the `for`/`since`/`until` section, `consume_next_arg = true` is set before calling `next_token`. Under normal flow this forces the next call to return a `TERM`. However, if the current argument is exhausted and `arg_i == arg_end` when `next_token` is entered (the outer arg-advance block, lines 93–100, runs before the `consume_next_arg` check), the code advances `begin` to the next argument and resets `arg_i`/`arg_end`. *Only then* does it reach the `consume_next_arg` branch — so this is generally correct. But there is one bypass path: a quoted pattern (`'`, `\"`, `/`) at the start of the next argument is handled in Phase 1 of `next_token` (lines 111–134) *before* Phase 2 (the `consume_next_arg` check, line 139). So the input:\n\n```\nfor 'something'\n```\n\n...causes the `for` loop to consume `'something'` as a quoted TERM — fine so far. But:\n\n```\nfor (food)\n```\n\n...causes `(` to be consumed as `LPAREN` in Phase 3 (line 163–167), returning `LPAREN` rather than `TERM`, crashing the assert. In release builds (`-DNDEBUG`), the assert is a no-op: `tok.kind` is `LPAREN`, `tok.value` is empty, the code then dereferences `*tok.value` at line 662 — undefined behavior via dereferencing an empty `optional<string>`.\n\n**Recommendation.** Replace the `assert` with a proper runtime check and throw a `parse_error`:\n\n```cpp\ntok = lexer.next_token(tok_context);\nif (tok.kind != lexer_t::token_t::TERM)\n    throw_(parse_error, _(\"Expected date term after 'for'/'since'/'until'\"));\n```\n\n---\n\n### Finding 4 — HIGH: Unbounded Recursion via Nested Parentheses (Stack Exhaustion)\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.cc`, line 472\n\n```cpp\ncase lexer_t::token_t::LPAREN:\n    node = parse_query_expr(tok_context, true);\n```\n\nEach `(` in the query causes one recursive call through the full parse chain: `parse_query_term` -> `parse_query_expr` -> `parse_or_expr` -> `parse_and_expr` -> `parse_unary_expr` -> `parse_query_term`. That is ~5 stack frames per nesting level. A user providing the query `((((((....))))))))` with 10,000 levels of nesting can exhaust the stack. This is reachable directly from the command line: `ledger bal '((((food))))'`.\n\nThere is no depth limit anywhere in the parser. The only protection is the OS stack guard page, which terminates the process with `SIGSEGV` rather than a clean error message.\n\n**Recommendation.** Add a depth counter passed through the parse calls (or a parser-level member), and throw `parse_error` when depth exceeds a safe limit (e.g., 200). This is a standard technique in recursive-descent parsers:\n\n```cpp\nif (++depth > MAX_PARSE_DEPTH)\n    throw_(parse_error, _(\"Query expression nested too deeply\"));\n```\n\n---\n\n### Finding 5 — MEDIUM: Silent Expression Injection via `expr` Keyword — No Input Validation\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.cc`, lines 365–366\n\n```cpp\ncase lexer_t::token_t::TOK_EXPR:\n    node = expr_t(*tok.value).get_op();\n```\n\nThe `expr` keyword passes its argument directly to the full Ledger expression parser (`expr_t`) without any sanitization. The `expr_t` parser can call arbitrary Ledger functions (file I/O via format strings, `system()` via expression builtins, scope lookups, etc.). While this is intentional for power users, it means any code path that constructs a `query_t` from partially-trusted input (e.g., a journal file that generates queries, a scripting interface, or a future network-facing feature) becomes a full expression injection. The catch blocks at lines 420–430 only apply to the `>[` / `<[` syntax, not to `expr`-context terms.\n\n**Recommendation.** For the rewrite, document this trust boundary explicitly. If `query_t` will ever be called with input that did not come directly from the trusted command line, add a flag to disable `TOK_EXPR` processing and throw `parse_error` when it is encountered. At minimum, add a comment marking this as a deliberate privileged code path.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 6 — MEDIUM: Unhandled Regex Compilation Exceptions Propagate as Untyped Exceptions to the Caller\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/mask.cc`, lines 362–371; called from `query.cc` lines 379 and 461\n\n`mask_t::operator=` calls `boost::regex::assign()` (or `boost::make_u32regex()`), which throws `boost::regex_error` (derived from `std::runtime_error`) on an invalid pattern. This exception propagates uncaught through `parse_query_term`, `parse_and_expr`, `parse_or_expr`, and `parse_query_expr`. None of these have `try`/`catch` blocks for regex errors.\n\nThe result is that a user query containing an invalid regex pattern — e.g., `ledger bal '[unclosed'` — throws a `boost::regex_error` that unwinds the full parse stack. In the current code, `expr_t::op_t` nodes may have been partially constructed and partially linked before the throw. Because those nodes are managed by `intrusive_ptr` (`ptr_op_t`), their destructors *are* run during stack unwinding, so memory is not leaked. However, the exception type visible to the caller is `boost::regex_error`, not the Ledger-internal `parse_error`, which may produce an ugly or misleading error message.\n\n**Recommendation.** Wrap the `mask_t` construction calls in `parse_query_term` with a catch block that re-throws as `parse_error`:\n\n```cpp\ntry {\n    mask->set_value(mask_t(*tok.value));\n} catch (const boost::regex_error& e) {\n    throw_(parse_error, _f(\"Invalid regex pattern '%1%': %2%\") % *tok.value % e.what());\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### Finding 7 — MEDIUM: `unbalanced_braces` Integer `balance` Can Overflow on Adversarial Input\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.cc`, lines 70–79\n\n```cpp\nint balance = 0;\nfor (const char& c : str) {\n    if (c == '(') ++balance;\n    else if (c == ')') if (--balance < 0) return true;\n}\n```\n\n`balance` is `int`. A string of `INT_MAX` opening parentheses causes signed integer overflow, which is undefined behavior in C++. On a 32-bit build with INT_MAX = 2,147,483,647, a string with 2^31 `(` characters would be needed — impractical from the command line. On 64-bit with `int` still 32-bit, the string would need to be 2 GB, also impractical from direct command-line use. However, if query terms can be read from journal files or other sources, this ceiling is lower. Additionally, the function is called from inside the identifier-accumulation loop at line 226, which means it is called once per `)` encountered in an identifier being scanned in `TOK_EXPR` context — the argument to `unbalanced_braces` is the partial identifier built so far.\n\n**Recommendation.** Change `balance` to `std::size_t` or add an early return if `balance > some_max_depth`. Since the function's only purpose is to detect imbalance (not count nesting), capping at a reasonable depth (e.g., 1000) is sufficient and eliminates the overflow.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 8 — MEDIUM: `token_cache` Double-Push Assertion Is a Runtime No-op in Release Builds\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.h`, lines 335–338\n\n```cpp\nvoid push_token(const token_t& tok) {\n    assert(token_cache.kind == token_t::UNKNOWN);\n    token_cache = tok;\n}\n```\n\n`push_token` is called from three parser functions after consuming a token that turns out to belong to a higher-level rule. If two `push_token` calls occur without an intervening `next_token`, the second silently overwrites the first. In release builds the assert is removed, so the dropped token causes silently wrong parse results — the parser may construct an incorrect expression tree without any error being raised.\n\n**Recommendation.** Replace the `assert` with a non-fatal runtime throw:\n\n```cpp\nvoid push_token(const token_t& tok) {\n    if (token_cache.kind != token_t::UNKNOWN)\n        throw_(parse_error, _(\"Internal error: token cache overrun\"));\n    token_cache = tok;\n}\n```\n\nThis converts a logic bug into a visible error in release builds, preventing silent mis-parsing.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 9 — LOW: ReDoS Risk via User-Controlled Regex Patterns Passed to `mask_t`\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.cc`, lines 379, 390, 461; `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/mask.h`\n\nEvery bare term and metadata pattern is compiled as a full Perl-compatible regex with `boost::regex::perl | boost::regex::icase`. A user can provide a crafted pattern such as `(a+)+b` or `^(([a-zA-Z])+\\s?)+$` that exhibits exponential backtracking when matched against long account names. Since Ledger evaluates the regex against every posting in the journal (potentially millions), a single malicious pattern in a query can cause the process to hang.\n\nThis is classified as low because Ledger is a single-user command-line tool and the input comes from the same user who controls the journal. However, if `query_t` is ever called from a multi-user context (e.g., a web frontend, a daemon, or an automated report system that accepts query strings from external sources), this becomes a medium-severity DoS vector.\n\n**Recommendation.** For the rewrite, consider adding an option to compile patterns with a regex engine that provides guaranteed linear-time matching (e.g., RE2 via `boost::xpressive` with certain flags, or the `re2` library). At minimum, document the trust assumption that query patterns come from the local user.\n\n---\n\n### Finding 10 — LOW: `lexer_t` Constructor Assert `begin != end` Is Release-Stripped\n\n**Location:** `/Users/johnw/src/ledger/query-parser/src/query.h`, lines 311–313\n\n```cpp\nassert(begin != end);\narg_i = (*begin).as_string().begin();\narg_end = (*begin).as_string().end();\n```\n\nIf `begin == end` in a release build, the assert is skipped, `*begin` dereferences an end-iterator (UB), and `arg_i`/`arg_end` are set to garbage. All callers do check `args.empty()` before constructing the lexer via `parser_t`, so this should not be reachable in practice. But the constructor itself provides no hard guarantee.\n\n**Recommendation.** Replace the `assert` with a proper check-and-throw, or document via a `[[expects]]` attribute that the contract requires non-empty input.\n\n---\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| # | Severity | Location | Issue |\n|---|----------|----------|-------|\n| 1 | Critical | `query.h:418` | `parser_t` copy ctor copies lexer iterators that alias the *source* `args` storage, causing dangling iterators if the source is d